{"title_page": "Sex trafficking in China", "text_new": "'''Sex trafficking in China''' is [[human trafficking]] for the purpose of [[Sexual slavery|sexual exploitation and slavery]] that occurs in the [[People's Republic of China]]. China, the world's most populous country, has one of the highest rates of human trafficking, including sex trafficking, in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailysignal.com/2014/11/20/nearly-two-thirds-human-trafficking-victims-asia/|title=Nearly Two-Thirds of Human Trafficking Victims Are from Asia|date=September 11, 2014|website=The Daily Signal}}</ref> It is a country of origin, destination, and transit for sexually trafficked persons.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://un-act.org/china/|title=China, The Trafficking Situation|website=United Nations Action for Cooperation Against Trafficking in Persons (UN-ACT)}}</ref> \n\nSex trafficking victims in the country are from all [[List of ethnic groups in China|ethnic groups in China]] and foreigners. [[Chinese people|Chinese citizens]], primarily women and girls, have been sex trafficked to the various [[provinces of China]], as well as other countries in [[Asia]] and different [[continents]]. They have been detected in [[overseas Chinese]] expatriate communities.<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/2188327/florida-sex-spas-chinese-human-trafficking-rings|title=In Florida sex spas, Chinese human trafficking rings operated in plain sight|date=March 2, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1 /> China's internal migrant population, in the hundreds of millions, is particularly vulnerable to sex trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/reports/2018-trafficking-in-persons-report/china/|title=2018 Trafficking in Persons Report: China|website=United States Department of State}}</ref> Sex trafficked victims are forced into prostitution, marriages, and or pregnancies.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> They are threatened<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/cnainsider/vietnam-kidnapped-brides-trafficking-china-wives-11777162|title=Raped, beaten and sold in China: Vietnam's kidnapped young brides|date=August 3, 2019|website=Channel News Asia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-21/vietnam-sapa-women-trafficked-to-china/9675610|title=Vietnamese teen's escape from the China trafficking trade that sold her mother|date=September 18, 2018|website=ABC News}}</ref> and physically and psychologically harmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theaseanpost.com/article/myanmars-trafficked-brides|title=Myanmar\u2019s trafficked brides|date=March 31, 2019|website=The ASEAN Post}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2014/11/sex-trafficking-and-chinas-one-child-policy/|title=Sex Trafficking and China's One Child Policy|date=November 6, 2014|website=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/sold-raped-enslaved-human-trafficking-victims-shared-stories-in-2019-4030004.html|title=Sold, raped, enslaved: Human trafficking victims shared stories in 2019|date=December 24, 2019|website=VnExpress}}</ref> They contract [[sexually transmitted diseases]] from rapes, and abuse and starvation are common. Some women and girls are tortured<ref name=autogenerated14>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/oppressed-enslaved-brutalised-women-trafficked-north-korea-chinas/|title=Oppressed, enslaved and brutalised: The women trafficked from North Korea into China's sex trade|date=May 20, 2019|website=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated13>{{cite web|url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/vietnam-china-human-trafficking-growing-malady/|title=Vietnam-China human trafficking a growing malady|date=November 24, 2013|website=New Europe}}</ref> and or murdered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/01/22/world/asia/china-sex-slaves-execution/index.html|title=China executes man who kept 6 women in dungeon as sex slaves|date=January 22, 2014|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-crime/chinese-man-sentenced-to-death-in-sex-slave-murder-case-idUSBRE8AT0CL20121130|title=Chinese man sentenced to death in sex slave murder case|date=November 30, 2012|website=Reuters}}</ref> \n\nSex trafficking and exploitation have permeated all levels of Chinese society. Male and female perpetrators in China come from a wide range of backgrounds and every social class. A number of traffickers are members of or facilitated by criminal organizations and gangs. Some government officials and workers, as well as foreigners, have profited from sex trafficking in China.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Rising incomes in China have spurred increased consumption of many services, both licit and illicit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/news/brief/colombia-china-sex-trafficking-network-uncovered/|title=Colombia to China Sex Trafficking Bust Illustrates Dynamics of Trade|date=August 25, 2017|website=InSight Crime}}</ref> It has occurred in businesses linked to [[Tourism in China|China's entertainment and tourism industries]]. Some reporters suggest that the [[Belt and Road Initiative]] and [[globalization]] have led to an increase in sex trafficking in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/3050632/bride-trafficking-hitch-chinas-belt-and-road|title=Bride trafficking, a problem on China's belt and road|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/south-asia/article/3041898/abused-raped-and-unfed-heart-wrenching-stories-pakistani|title=Abused, raped: heart-wrenching stories of Pakistani brides trafficked to China|date=December 13, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> Chinese sex traffickers operate throughout the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/thai-surrogate-chinese-arrested-illegal-surrogacy-raid-12432510|title=7 Thai surrogates, 2 Chinese nationals arrested in illegal surrogacy raid in Bangkok|date=February 13, 2020|website=CNA}}</ref>\nCybersex trafficking is a growing problem in twenty-first century China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/13/world/asia/north-korea-cybersex-china.html|title=After Fleeing North Korea, Women Get Trapped as Cybersex Slaves in China|date=September 13, 2019|website=The New York Times}}</ref> The global spread of high-speed internet and increase in computer, tablet, and smart phone ownership have fueled online or virtual forced prostitution and sex abuse and the creation of illegal pornographic videos purchased by users worldwide.\n\nThe scale of sex trafficking in China is difficult to know because of the lack of primary research and data collection, the clandestine nature of sex trafficking crimes, the fact that only a small minority of cases are reported to the authorities, and other factors.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Chinese government ministries as well as international and domestic agencies and organisations do some work to combat sex trafficking patterns, but this has not brought substantive improvements and responses have proved insufficient.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The enforcement of sex trafficking laws and investigating and prosecuting of trafficking cases have been immobilized by interagency collaboration and coordination challenges, logistical difficulties, poor border management,<ref name=autogenerated13 /> language barriers of foreign victims, political dynamics, corruption, and apathy.<ref name=autogenerated9>{{cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/interview/why-beijing-fails-fight-human-trafficking|title=Why Beijing Fails to Fight Human Trafficking|website=Council on Foreign Relations}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/trafficking-survivors-failed-world-190801143149035.html|title=Trafficking survivors are being failed the world over|website=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/10/chinas-bride-trafficking-problem/|title=China's Bride Trafficking Problem|date=October 30, 2019|website=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated18>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2019/05/16/North-Korea-women-in-China-trapped-in-sex-trade/7621557980738/|title=North Korea women in China trapped in sex trade|date=May 16, 2019|website=UPI}}</ref> Some Chinese police and officials, as well as overseas embassies and [[diplomatic missions]],<ref name=autogenerated17>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1236534/no-reply-from-chinese-embassy-on-pogo-sex-trade-hontiveros|title=No reply from Chinese Embassy on POGO sex trade \u2014 Hontiveros|date=March 4, 2019|website=Inquirer}}</ref> have been accused of negligence concerning counter-sex trafficking efforts and concern for victims.<ref name=autogenerated16>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2019/03/myanmar-chinas-bride-trafficking-problem/|title=Myanmar and China's Bride Trafficking Problem|date=March 22, 2019|website=Inter Press Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/news/brief/colombia-china-sex-trafficking-network-uncovered/|title=Colombia to China Sex Trafficking Bust Illustrates Dynamics of Trade|date=August 25, 2017|website=InSight Crime}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/07/chinas-trafficked-brides/|title=China\u2019s Trafficked Brides|date=July 19, 2017|website=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Available statistics indicate that China needs to devote greater resources and implement better policies and strategies designed to reduce sex trafficking in the country.<ref name=autogenerated9 /> It is difficult for [[List of the largest trading partners of China|trading partners of China]] to criticize the country's inadequate anti-sex trafficking efforts because of fears of tensions.<ref name=autogenerated5 />  Chinese  civil society's efforts in countering sex trafficking are stymied by threats and coercion from criminal organizations and officials and the government's repression of women and human rights organizations, presses, and lawyers.<ref name=autogenerated9 /><ref name=autogenerated5 />  \n\n==Victims==\n[[File:China administrative.svg |upright=1.4|thumbnail|right|Chinese citizen and foreign victims are sex trafficked into and out of all [[provinces of China]]. They are raped and physically and psychologically harmed in other ways in homes, brothels, indirect sex establishments, and various business and work sites within these administrative divisions.]] \n\nVictims of sex trafficking for [[sexual slavery in China]] include, but are not limited to, children, impoverished, migrants, disabled persons, ethnic and religious minorities, foreigners, and overseas Chinese. It is not uncommon for victims of rape to be used additionally as forced laborers in homes, farms, and businesses.<ref name=autogenerated16 /> They, particularly forced prostitutes, often contract sexually transmitted diseases because the rapers do not wear condoms.<ref name=autogenerated13 /> Women and girls have contracted [[HIV]].<ref name=autogenerated19>{{cite web|url=https://www.gospelherald.com/articles/49719/20131127/compelled-by-love-the-church-in-china-fights-human-trafficking-part-ii.htm|title=Compelled by Love: The Church in China Fights Human Trafficking, Part II|date=November 27, 2013|website=The Gosepl Herald Society}}</ref> A number are verbally and physically abused and beaten,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caritas.org/2017/11/poverty-and-conflict-in-myanmar-fuel-human-trafficking/|title=POVERTY AND CONFLICT IN MYANMAR FUEL HUMAN TRAFFICKING|website=Caritas}}</ref> starved, drugged,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/04/17/asia/vietnamese-girls-child-brides-china/index.html|title=Vietnamese girls smuggled into China and sold as child brides|date=April 19, 2016|website=CNN World}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vietnaminsider.vn/vietnamese-trafficking-victims-shared-their-stories/|title=Vietnamese trafficking victims shared their stories|date=December 25, 2019|website=Vietnam Insider}}</ref> and sexually tortured.<ref name=autogenerated13 /><ref name=autogenerated14 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/vietnamese-trafficking-victim-reveals-heartbreaking-ordeal|title=Vietnamese Trafficking Victim Reveals Heartbreaking Ordeal|date=September 24, 2015|website=VOA News}}</ref> Many sex trafficked women and girls are never found.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n  \nSurviving victims face ostracization from their families and communities.<ref name=autogenerated12>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5555695/china-women-trafficking-myanmar/|title=A Shortage of Women in China Has Led to the Trafficking of 'Brides' From Myanmar, Says a Report|date=March 21, 2019|website=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Some victims are discouraged by family and friends from seeking justice. Some, suffering from trauma or forced drug addiction because of their captors and in extreme poverty, reluctantly return to prostitution after being rescued.<ref name=autogenerated19 /> Many mothers who fled or were rescued will never be able to see their children held by the buying family or sold by the traffickers.<ref name=autogenerated1a>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/oppressed-enslaved-brutalised-women-trafficked-north-korea-chinas/|title=Oppressed, enslaved and brutalised: The women trafficked from North Korea into China's sex trade|date=May 20, 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph|last1=Smith|first1=Nicola|last2=Farmer|first2=Ben}}</ref> \nSome former trafficking victims are reluctant to report traffickers to the local authorities because they fear reprisal from criminals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/11/vietnams-human-trafficking-problem-is-too-big-to-ignore/|title=Vietnam's Human Trafficking Problem Is Too Big to Ignore|date=November 8, 2019|website=The Diplomat}}</ref>  \nSome recused victims get abducted and sex trafficked again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/thousands-of-myanmar-women-forced-into-marriages-in-china/a-46625465|title=Thousands of Myanmar women forced into marriages in China|date=July 12, 2018|website=DW News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/21/interview-why-brides-myanmar-are-trafficked-china#|title=Interview: Why \u2018Brides\u2019 From Myanmar Are Trafficked to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\nTrafficking survivors may need urgent medical care for problems ranging from injuries due to abuse to sexual and reproductive health needs. They need shelter as sometimes they cannot return to families that were complicit in their trafficking. They need legal assistance to ensure that the justice system - which too often lets trafficking victims down - is responsive to their needs for accountability and compensation. Many need financial assistance as months and years of sexual slavery resulted in no education and income.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/08/05/trafficking-survivors-are-being-failed-world-over#|title=Trafficking Survivors Are Being Failed the World Over|date=August 5, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese government's protection of victims has been criticized. Chinese law enforcement officials have arrested and detained foreign women on suspicion of prostitution crimes without screening them for indicators of sexual exploitation\u2014sometimes for as long as four months\u2014before deporting them for immigration violations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /> The police have treated the women and girls as violators of immigration law but have taken little action against the their traffickers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/thousands-of-myanmar-women-forced-into-marriages-in-china/a-46625465|title=Thousands of Myanmar women forced into marriages in China|date=July 12, 2018|website=DW News}}</ref>  \n\nThere is a need for a greater rehabilitative assistance and protection services, including comprehensive counseling and medical reintegration of the victims.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Detained or imprisoned women have beaten by other inmates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/oppressed-enslaved-brutalised-women-trafficked-north-korea-chinas/|title=Oppressed, enslaved and brutalised: The women trafficked from North Korea into China's sex trade|date=May 20, 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph|last1=Smith|first1=Nicola|last2=Farmer|first2=Ben}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese government maintains a wide network of shelters across the country, providing food, accommodation and other services to Chinese citizens facing various kinds of challenges. The system, however, is inexperienced in supporting foreigners in need of help. Anecdotal evidence suggests that foreigner women escaping conditions of forced marriage, some pregnant, are at times not granted access to shelters and their services. Specialist support services exist for children, including specialized shelters. Emergency shelters, physical and mental health services, education, job training, financial assistance, and family reunification are available for all groups.<ref name=autogenerated7>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalslaveryindex.org/2018/findings/highlights/|title=China Country Data|website=Global Slavery Index}}</ref> \n\n===Females===\nFemales are more vulnerable than males because of entrenched misogyny that causes men to inferiorize and commoditize women and girls.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> Traditional patriarchal structures reinforce gender inequality, especially in rural areas where females are oftentimes not afforded the same opportunities as males and are forced to submit to male authority. This inequality leaves women and girls increasingly marginalized and vulnerable to sex trafficking. \n\nThe [[one-child policy]] and preference for sons over daughters has led to a skewed sex ratio in which men outnumber women in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Consequently, there is an increase demand for trafficked prostitutes and wives in China. \n<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n   \n===Children===\nChildren have been targeted by perpetrators.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/07/chinas-trafficked-brides/|title=China\u2019s Trafficked Brides|date=July 19, 2017|website=The Diplomat}}</ref> Those from rural areas and migrant students, as well as [[Left-behind children in China|left-behind children]] whose parents have migrated to the cities and other countries, have been identified as a vulnerable population to sex trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=https://www.ecpat.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/3.-SECTT-CHINA.pdf|title=Global Study on Sexual Exploitation of Children in Travel and Tourism. Country-specific Report, China.|date=2015|website=ECPAT International}}</ref> Children who are [[Adoption fraud|illegal adopted]] are vulnerable to sexual exploitation.\n\n===People in poverty===\nSex traffickers in China often abduct or purchase women and girls from families in poverty or facing financial crisis, particularly the rural poor, because the victims often do not have any political power and connections and lack education about sex trafficking laws, which enables the captors to not attract much attention or publicity.<ref name=autogenerated16 />\n\n===Migrants===\nThe [[hukou]] household registration system in China has contributed to the vulnerability of internal migrants by limiting employment opportunities and reducing access to social services, particularly for Chinese victims returning from exploitation abroad.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Disabled persons===\nDisabled persons, including those with mental illness or who are deaf and mute, have been trafficked into and out of China by perpetrators.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Traffickers target adults and children with disabilities whose parents have left them with relatives to migrate to the cities.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Ethnic and religious minorities===\nWomen and girls from minority groups are at an increased risk of sex trafficking because population displacements and a lack of political representation, power, and protection.<ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref>\n\n===Foreigners===\nForeign women and girls from [[Mongolia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/mongolias-prostitution-zones-women-trade-sex-fuel-sub-zero-temperatures/|title=Mongolia's prostitution zones, where women trade sex for fuel in sub-zero temperatures|date=February 19, 2019|website=The Telegraph}}</ref> [[Vietnam]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/sold-raped-enslaved-human-trafficking-victims-shared-stories-in-2019-4030004.html|title=Sold, raped, enslaved: Human trafficking victims shared stories in 2019|date=December 24, 2019|website=VnExpress International}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated13 /> [[Cambodia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/106505/woman-accused-human-trafficking/|title=Woman accused of human trafficking|date=February 5, 2018|website=Khmer Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/64043/poverty-causes-trafficking-to-china-says-report/|title=Poverty Causes Trafficking to China, Says Report|date=September 1, 2016|website=Khmer Times}}</ref> [[Myanmar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/geopolitics/article/2176841/after-fleeing-violence-home-myanmese-women-face-forced|title=In China, thousands of Myanmar women are forced into childbirth|date=December 7, 2018|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> [[Thailand]], [[Malaysia]], [[Laos]], the [[Philippines]], [[Indonesia]], and other countries have been trafficked into China for sexual exploitation.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=https://www.cecc.gov/sites/chinacommission.house.gov/files/documents/CECC_ExecutiveSummary2019_FINAL_0.pdf|title=Congressional-Executive Commission on China 2019 Annual Report\u2014Executive Summary|website=Congressional-Executive Commission on China}}</ref> They experience difficulties being rescued because they do not speak Chinese and have no identification documents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3015603/chinese-police-free-more-1100-human-trafficking-victims-after|title=Chinese police free more than 1,100 human trafficking victims after targeting Southeast Asian networks|date=June 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> \n\nAuthorities continue to detain and deport [[North Korea]] sexually trafficked victims who may face severe punishment and/or death upon their repatriation.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The majority of North Korean refugees leaving the DPRK are women. The Chinese government's refusal to recognize these women as refugees denies them legal protection and may encourage the trafficking of North Korean women and girls within China. Many children born to Chinese fathers and North Korean mothers remain deprived of basic rights to education and other public services, owing to their lack of legal resident status in China, which constitute violations of the PRC Nationality Law and the Convention on the Rights of the Child.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n===Overseas Chinese===\nChinese women and girls are subjected to sex trafficking in countries throughout the world. Some are deceived into prostitution or confined to private homes where they are raped.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nMany Chinese victims sex trafficked into the [[United States]] are forced to work in brothels disguised as [[massage parlors]]. The conditions in these illegal establishments are sometimes appalling. Money collected by operators is transferred to superiors in China at times.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/20191214/orchids-of-asia-case-425k-in-cash-lots-in-100-bills-seized-by-police|title=Orchids of Asia case: $425K in cash, lots in $100 bills, seized by police|date=December 14, 2019|website=The Palm Beach Post}}</ref> \n\nChinese women and girls have been sex trafficked to cater to men involved with or working for [[Philippine Offshore Gaming Operators]].<ref name=autogenerated17 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/1817631|title=\u2018Probe Chinese group\u2019s sex trafficking activities\u2019|date=August 6, 2019|website=SunStar Cebu}}</ref>\n\nChinese victims have been sex trafficked to businesses catering to people seeing the [[Southeast Asian Games]] and other sports events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/lifestyle-culture/article/3041328/sea-games-foreign-tourist-surge-philippines-sees-rising|title=SEA Games: foreign tourist surge to Philippines sees rising risk of sex trafficking|date=December 10, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\n==Forced prostitution==\n[[File:Barber shop Bao'an Shenzhen China.jpg|300px|thumbnail|right|Chinese and foreign women and girls sex trafficked and forced into prostitution are raped in brothels and establishments similar to this one in [[South China]]. 'Online rape dens' in more inconspicuous premises are increasingly being used for digital and live pornographic video sharing in the twenty-first century.]]\n\nVictims are coerced by perpetrators by imposing large travel fees, confiscating passports,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caritas.org/2017/11/poverty-and-conflict-in-myanmar-fuel-human-trafficking/|title=POVERTY AND CONFLICT IN MYANMAR FUEL HUMAN TRAFFICKING|website=Caritas}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-vietnam-humantrafficking/trafficking-of-vietnamese-women-for-sex-and-marriage-expands-across-region-expert-idUSKCN0Y9180|title=Trafficking of Vietnamese women for sex and marriage expands across region: expert|date=May 18, 2016|website=Reuters}}</ref> confining victims, or are physically and financially threatened to compel their engagement in commercial sex.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Victims are deceived by traffickers and brothel operators by answering ads for jobs as waitresses, servers, cleaners, and more.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Some have been told they could study in universities and educational institutions at low costs only to be sold into prostitution.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Some are drugged<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/04/17/asia/vietnamese-girls-child-brides-china/index.html|title=Vietnamese girls smuggled into China and sold as child brides|date=April 19, 2016|website=CNN World}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/vietnamese-woman-trafficked-to-china-returns-home-after-22-years-3947636.html|title=Vietnamese woman trafficked to China returns home after 22 years|date=July 4, 2019|website=VnExpress}}</ref>   and abducted.<ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/sold-raped-enslaved-human-trafficking-victims-shared-stories-in-2019-4030004.html|title=Sold, raped, enslaved: Human trafficking victims shared stories in 2019|date=December 24, 2019|website=VnExpress}}</ref> The brothels are often indirect sex establishments, such as beer gardens, massage parlors, salons, karaoke bars, retail spaces, and non-commercial sites.<ref name=autogenerated8>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3006909/non-profit-group-which-helps-sex-trafficking-victims-seeks|title=Non-profit group, which helps sex-trafficking victims, seeks tie-ups with ethical business partners in Hong Kong|date=April 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref> Other locations include construction sites, remote mining and logging camps, and areas with high concentrations of Chinese migrant workers.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> \n\nWomen and girls who are trafficked into brothels are raped by hundreds of men.<ref name=autogenerated8 /> They are kept under strict surveillance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/vietnamese-trafficking-victim-reveals-heartbreaking-ordeal|title=Vietnamese Trafficking Victim Reveals Heartbreaking Ordeal|date=September 24, 2015|website=VOA News}}</ref> It is not uncommon for them to be guarded and tied or locked up and never allowed to go outside.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/sold-raped-enslaved-human-trafficking-victims-shared-stories-in-2019-4030004.html|title=Sold, raped, enslaved: Human trafficking victims shared stories in 2019|date=December 24, 2019|website=VnExpress}}</ref> Some are beaten and or contract sexually transmitted diseases. Others commit suicide.<ref name=autogenerated15>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/society/article/2151075/vietnam-without-love-child-brides-china|title=From Vietnam, without love: the child brides of China|date=June 17, 2018|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nThere are more males than females in China because of the one-child policy and preference. This may have led to an increase in the demand for prostitution.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> China's business culture also involves frequenting entertainment venues, some which have forced prostitutes.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n===Online rape dens===\nA number of sexually trafficked victims in China are habitually subjected to penetrative vaginal and anal rape, groping, and forced masturbation  live on camera in 'online rape dens.'<ref name=autogenerated18 /><ref name=autogenerated14 /> Gang rape occurs in these dens as well. Traffickers sell these videos and earn revenue by adding them to [[pornography]] websites.\n\n==Forced marriages and pregnancies==\nIllicit brokers increasingly facilitate the forced and fraudulent marriage, or bride trafficking, of Chinese women and foreigners to men in China and from abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/10/31/chinas-bride-trafficking-problem#|title=China's Bride Trafficking Problem|date=October 31, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /> These women are sexually exploited in the illegal marriages. The Chinese government's birth limitation policy and the cultural preference for sons have resulted in an uneven sex ratio, contributing substantially to the demand for brides from rural areas and outside of China.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nSome female trafficking victims are raped so they become surrogate mothers and bear children.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> There are testimonies that women and girls have also been injected with sperm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2019/7/compilation-trafficking-survivors-share-stories|title=Trafficked: Three survivors of human trafficking share their stories|date=July 29, 2019|website=UN Women}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Women,-children-and-babies:-human-trafficking-to-China-is-on-the-rise-47513.html|title=Women, children and babies: human trafficking to China is on the rise|date=July 11, 2019|website=Asia News}}</ref> Their children are kept by the captors, the paying husband, or sold to other families.<ref name=autogenerated12 /> Some husbands let other men, including his relatives, rape his trafficked wife.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/ad6b5fb667ca449d8cadc05bb2bc0a41|title=Pakistani police target traffickers selling brides to China|date=June 17, 2019|website=AP News}}</ref> Some women and girls who have been trafficked to entire families of men, who are poor and pool their money together to buy one wife.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vietcetera.com/en/pacific-links-foundation-the-battle-against-human-trafficking/|title=Pacific Links Foundation: The Battle Against Human Trafficking|date=August 7, 2017|website=Vietcetera}}</ref>  \n\n==Industries==\n\n===Entertainment and tourism industries===\nChina's [[Tourism in China|entertainment and tourism industries]] have developed rapidly with the country's economic growth. Victims are trafficked into businesses, including restaurants, bars, casinos, and nightclubs, linked to these industries.<ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.china.org.cn/opinion/2014-02/20/content_31532335.htm|title=Earnest bid to end sex trade|date=February 20, 2014|website=China Org}}</ref>\n\n===Mining industry===\nWomen and girls are trafficked to mining sector sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/mongolias-prostitution-zones-women-trade-sex-fuel-sub-zero-temperatures/|title=Mongolia's prostitution zones, where women trade sex for fuel in sub-zero temperatures|date=February 19, 2019|website=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Special administrative regions of China==\nChinese [[Mainland Chinese|mainlanders]] are sex trafficked into the [[special administrative regions of China]]. Women and girls within these administrative regions are also trafficked to other parts of the city or to mainland cities.    \n\n===Hong Kong===\n{{Main|Sex trafficking in Hong Kong}}\n\nMainland Chinese women and girls are [[Sex trafficking in Hong Kong|sex trafficked into Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Making-a-difference/Change-Agent/2015/1022/New-ways-to-help-Hong-Kong-s-human-trafficking-victims|title=New ways to help Hong Kong's human trafficking victims|date=October 22, 2015|website=CN Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/article/1901109/human-trafficking-hong-kong-hidden-plain-sight|title=Human trafficking in Hong Kong: hidden in plain sight|date=January 16, 2016|website=South China Morning Post Magazine}}</ref> They are forced into prostitution in brothels, homes, and businesses in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Making-a-difference/Change-Agent/2015/1022/New-ways-to-help-Hong-Kong-s-human-trafficking-victims|title=New ways to help Hong Kong's human trafficking victims|date=October 22, 2015|website=CN Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/article/1901109/human-trafficking-hong-kong-hidden-plain-sight|title=Human trafficking in Hong Kong: hidden in plain sight|date=January 16, 2016|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-crime/article/2134591/fed-human-trafficking-hong-kong-migrant-workers-hold-vigil|title=Fed up with human trafficking, Hong Kong migrant workers hold vigil demanding justice|date=February 25, 2018|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1986535/hong-kong-must-lead-fight-against-human-trafficking-rather|title=Hong Kong must lead the fight against human trafficking, rather than just do the bare minimum|date=July 8, 2016|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Global Slavery Index]], the [[Hong Kong]] Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China has a 'weak response' to modern slavery, including sexual slavery, relative to [[gross domestic product]] based on [[purchasing power parity]].<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\n===Macau===\n{{Main|Sex trafficking in Macau}}\nMainland Chinese victims are [[Sex trafficking in Hong Kong|sex trafficked into Macau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macaubusiness.com/macaus-ranking-upgraded-in-us-human-trafficking-report-govt-dismisses-untrue-conclusions/|title=Macau\u2019s ranking upgraded in US human trafficking report, Gov\u2019t dismisses \u2018untrue\u2019 conclusions|date=June 21, 2019|website=Macau Business}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plataformamedia.com/en-uk/news/society/human-trafficking-is-still-a-big-problem-in-macau-hong-kong-newspaper-says-11428089.html|title=Human trafficking is still a big problem in Macau, Hong Kong newspaper says|date=October 21, 2019|website=Plataforma}}</ref> They are sex slaves in brothels and hotel rooms near the casinos and other entertainment venues. \n\n==China\u2013Mongolia border==\n{{See also|Sex trafficking in Mongolia}}\n\nChinese and Mongolian women and girls are sex trafficked to and through the [[China\u2013Mongolia border]] border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2009-07-22/stolen-mongolia-sex|title=Stolen from Mongolia for sex|date=July 22, 2009|website=PRI}}</ref> At the border and in the [[Gobi Desert]] are global mining sector and other heavy industry operations with large workforces of isolated men. These, including the ones in [[Tavan Tolgoi|Tavan Tolgoi coal deposits]]  have been a focal point for prostitution and sex trafficking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/mongolias-prostitution-zones-women-trade-sex-fuel-sub-zero-temperatures/|title=Mongolia's prostitution zones, where women trade sex for fuel in sub-zero temperatures|date=February 19, 2019|website=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Criminal organizations and perpetrators==\nDomestic and transnational criminal organizations operating in China are becoming more organized, professional, and diverse. Members of criminal organizations use fraudulent employment offers, threats, direct force, and kidnapping to trafficked victims into sexual exploitation and slavery. Some marriage brokers, matchmakers, mail-order bride service managers,  and loan sharks obtain women for criminal organizations.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Traffickers frequently take advantage of [[debt bondage]] to control their victims. They also threaten families back home to ensure the victims continue to cooperate. <ref name=autogenerated11>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/11/vietnams-human-trafficking-problem-is-too-big-to-ignore/|title=Vietnam's Human Trafficking Problem Is Too Big to Ignore|date=November 8, 2019|website=The Diplomat}}</ref> \n\nChinese government officials and businessmen, facilitated by criminal organizations, have been arrested for participating in forcible commercial sexual exploitation.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> There are government officials who facilitate or are complicit in sex trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nFemales perpetrators are sometimes victims of trafficking themselves and are coerced to abduct more women and girls for their captors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.irrawaddy.com/article.php?art_id=21486|title=A Grim Trade: Trafficking Palaung Women to China|date=June 14, 2011|website=The Irrawaddy}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref> Female traffickers can better conceal their identities to the police and win trust from victims more easily compared with their male counterparts.<ref name=autogenerated13 />\n\nFamily members, relatives, friends, classmates, colleagues, or acquaintances sometimes sell girls to sex traffickers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated16 /><ref name=autogenerated15 />\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/525900/child-trafficking-in-china-often-starts-with-parents-selling-their-own-kids/|title=Child trafficking in China often starts with parents selling their own kids|date=October 16, 2015|website=Quartz}}</ref> The girls' parents or the trafficker may take her to the hospital to get a [[virginity test]].<ref name=autogenerated8 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/21/interview-why-brides-myanmar-are-trafficked-china#|title=Interview: Why \u2018Brides\u2019 From Myanmar Are Trafficked to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/world/region/2020/01/554485/1807-human-trafficking-victims-rescued-thailand-2019|title=1,807 human trafficking victims rescued in Thailand in 2019|date=January 8, 2020|website=New Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nSome sex traffickers impersonate police officers to gain victims' trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/80-percent-of-vietnamese-human-trafficking-victims-end-up-in-china-3960605.html|title=80 percent of Vietnamese human trafficking victims end up in China|date=August 1, 2019|website=VnExpress International}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref> \n\nPerpetrators are motivated by monetary incentives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vietcetera.com/en/pacific-links-foundation-the-battle-against-human-trafficking/|title=Pacific Links Foundation: The Battle Against Human Trafficking|date=August 7, 2017|website=Vietcetera}}</ref> \n\n===Online deception===\nPerpetrators in China use the internet, gaming sites, social media, [[WeChat]], [[Telegram]], and other messaging apps to lure victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2020/03/01/washington-county-charges-offer-glimpse-into-the-secret-world-of-chinese-sex-trafficking/|title=Washington County charges offer glimpse into the secret world of Chinese sex trafficking|date=March 1, 2020|website=Twin Cities Pioneer Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/news/2016/09/02/vietnam-wakes-its-human-trafficking-problem|title=Vietnam wakes up to its human trafficking problem|date=September 2, 2016|website=The New Humanitarian}}</ref> Male traffickers often entice females with phony online dating relationships and persuade them to move to a different province or abroad, then subject them to sexual slavery.<ref name=autogenerated11 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref>    \n\n==Unreported crimes==\nA criminologist in the [[People's Public Security University of China]], stated, \u201cbehind\nevery reported sex abuse case, there might be six hidden cases unreported\u201d.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Victims might be fearful and or ashamed to report a sex crime. Children and mentally disabled persons might not be even aware that such illegal acts has been committed against them.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Some brothels with sex trafficked victims operate underground.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Data collection of sex trafficking crimes in China have been flawed which has led to incidents not being reported.\n\n==Legal framework==\nVictims were legally entitled to request criminal prosecution and claim financial restitution through civil lawsuits against their traffickers.<ref name=autogenerated7 /> \n\nChina has not signed, ratified, acceded to the Convention to Suppress the Slave Trade and Slavery or [[Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery]]. It has for the [[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, Especially Women and Children]], [[Optional Protocol on the Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography]]\n \nArticle 240 of the [[Chinese law|Chinese Criminal Code]] criminalized the \u201cabducting and trafficking of women or children.\u201d Article 244 criminalized the forcing of a person \u201cto work by violence, threat or restriction of personal freedom\u201d and recruiting, transporting, or otherwise assisting in forcing others to labor. Article 358 criminalized forced prostitution. Under the provisions of article 296 of the Criminal Code, a person who enslaves another or places him in a position without freedom, similar to slavery, shall be punished with imprisonment for not less than one and not more than seven years. Article 359 criminalized harboring prostitution or seducing or introducing others into prostitution.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nThe Chinese government maintained insufficient law enforcement efforts of sex trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> It has been recommended that China vigorously investigate, prosecute, and impose prison sentences on perpetrators of sex trafficking; update the legal framework concerning the criminzaliztion of sex trafficking, including the facilitation of prostitution involving children younger than the age of 18; expand efforts to institute proactive, formal procedures to systematically identify trafficking victims throughout the country; train front-line officers on their implementation; cease penalization of victims for acts committed as a direct result of being subjected to sex trafficking; ensure authorities do not subject trafficking victims to detention, punishment, or forcible repatriation; increase the transparency of government efforts to combat trafficking and provide disaggregated data on investigations and prosecutions, victim identification, and service provision, including by continuing to share relevant data with international partners.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==Anti-sex trafficking mechanisms==\nChina has a \u201cNational Plan of Action on Combating Trafficking in Women and Children.\u201d The Ministry of Public Security, Ministry of Civil Affairs, Supreme People's Court, and All China Women's Federation have issued various joint policies on prosecution, prevention and victim protection. The Inter-Ministerial Joint Meeting Mechanism (IMJMM) holds annual and thematic meetings as well as information sharing on a monthly basis. Anti-sex trafficking campaigns have been disseminated through television, print media and online platforms. Numerous documentaries and animations have been produced and broadcast to raise awareness among the general public.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nCoordinated Mekong Ministerial Initiative against Trafficking (COMMIT) Task Force (2005), with UN-ACT as secretariat. Chinese law enforcement carries out hotspot policing conducted in high risk areas and joint border operations conducted with law enforcement counterparts in Vietnam and Myanmar. A team of interpreters for Greater Mekong Sub-region (GMS) languages has been established to support cross-border case investigations.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAn \u201cOperational Guide for Anti-Trafficking Police\u201d has been established and is currently used by police officers.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nSeveral projects have been initiated by the All China Women's Federation (ACWF) to prevent trafficking among migrant populations in various source and destination provinces.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nShelters provide interim care to trafficking victims with managers and staff in most provinces having received training (Ministry of Civil Affairs). An operational guide to assist victims of trafficking has been developed and distributed to all shelters.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===Official and police training=== \nTraining for police, teachers, social workers, labor inspectors, immigration officials, shelter managers, marriage registration officials, and other government workers has taken place on basic legal frameworks surrounding sexual slavery and victim identification. In conjunction with an international organisation, authorities sponsored and participated in trainings on victim identification and assistance for consular officials and law enforcement, regulation of marriage migration, and interagency implementation of the national referral mechanism. The Ministry of Public Security promulgated written instructions to law enforcement officers throughout the country with the aim of clarifying procedures for identifying victims among individuals in prostitution and those who may be subjected to exploitation via forced or fraudulent marriage. The government reported funding training in rural areas for court officials and prosecutors; however, it did not provide detailed information on these efforts. In addition, law enforcement officials, prosecutors, and judges attended trainings on trafficking organized by other countries and international organizations; when authorities participated in these trainings, the PRC sometimes provided speakers and venues, and funded lodging, transportation, and meals for some participants.The office to combat trafficking in persons developed and approved trafficking victim identification procedures and disseminated them to law enforcement officials throughout the country. The government acknowledged that victim identification procedures varied according to local officials' training and understanding of trafficking; this variation increased the risk that unidentified trafficking victims were detained and deported following arrest for unlawful acts committed as a direct result of being subjected to human trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\n===Public education===\nPublic education about sex crimes in China exists but is insufficient. Many Chinese children receive little information about sexual offences and have a weak awareness or capability to protect themselves from such offences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ecpat.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/3.-SECTT-CHINA.pdf|title=Global Study on Sexual Exploitation of Children in Travel and Tourism. Country-specific Report, China.|date=2015|website=ECPAT Intercriminalovernational}}</ref>\n\nChina's highest-rated television channel ran broadcasts raising awareness on trafficking. The government  disseminates some anti-trafficking messages in train and bus stations and through media such as cell phones, television, and the internet. Through China's social media platforms, such as [[Sina Weibo]], the Ministry of Public Security reported using its official microblog to raise awareness of trafficking and receive information from the public regarding suspected trafficking cases. In 2018, the Ministry of Public Security reportedly sent 350,000 police officers to public schools to educate children about the risks of exploitation. Article highlights announcement of rescued children on Weibo, a popular Chinese microblogging platform, accompanied by photos of them. At the end of the article, tips and reminders are provided for readers on what to do if they suspect any instance of child trafficking or abduction. A link is also provided to the National Abduction and Family Search Platform, which acts as a directory for abducted and trafficked children.<ref name=autogenerated10>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalslaveryindex.org/2019/data/country-data/china/|title=China Country Data|date=2019|website=Global Slavery Index}}</ref>\n\nThe two Women's Federations and the Publicity Department focus on raising awareness and provide assistance with victim support. They run annual campaigns that focus on school curricula, television ads and transportation hubs, especially around the time of the Spring Festival. \n\n===Reporting===\nGovernment websites provide list of relevant agencies and departments and their hotlines. Several of the most popular apps in China have the additional function of helping locate missing persons through localized push notifications. Scores of specialist apps for registering family members young and old or reporting suspected child trafficking have also been appearing in the country's app stores. The free, 24/7 dial 110 nationwide police calling system allows victims or witnesses to obtain assistance from the police.<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n==Government response problems==\nAccording to [[Human Rights Watch]], Chinese law enforcement officers in certain jurisdictions make little effort to save sex trafficking victims.<ref name=autogenerated12 />\n\nThere has been not been an increase in public reports of sexual slavery cases in recent years. The Ministry of Public Security has not reported the number of investigations initiated into possible trafficking cases.<ref name=autogenerated10 /> \n\nThe reporting mechanisms (websites, hotline, etc.) do operate in multiple languages.<ref name=autogenerated10 />  \n\nTraining for first responders of trafficking crimes is not delivered systematically and at regular intervals. Reports suggest that screening procedures exist but it is unclear if these have been distributed to all first res ponders or concern both victim screening and identification.\n<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n==Corruption== \nSome government officials and police have been complicit in sex trafficking. Some police have demanded bribes in order to return victims to their families.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/thousands-of-myanmar-women-forced-into-marriages-in-china/a-46625465|title=Thousands of Myanmar women forced into marriages in China|date=July 12, 2018|website=DW News}}</ref>\n\n==Government human rights violations==\n{{Main|Human rights in China}}\nThe Chinese government's human rights violations have hampered anti-sex trafficking initiatives.<ref name=autogenerated9 /> Sustained attacks on organizations and lawyers have resulted in victims not being able to seek justice.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\n==Anti-trafficking Organizations==\nThere are civil society organizations working to rescue women, but these organizations have limited resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/21/interview-why-brides-myanmar-are-trafficked-china#|title=Interview: Why \u2018Brides\u2019 From Myanmar Are Trafficked to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\nChristian organizations save sex trafficked victims in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Vietnams-modern-sex-slaves-sold-in-China-as-prostitutes-or-brides-33361.html|title=Vietnam's \"modern sex slaves\" sold in China as prostitutes or brides|date=February 3, 2015|website=Asia News}}</ref>\n\n[[Agape International Missions]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3006909/non-profit-group-which-helps-sex-trafficking-victims-seeks|title=Non-profit group, which helps sex-trafficking victims, seeks tie-ups with ethical business partners in Hong Kong|date=April 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> and [[Blue Dragon Children's Foundation]] save victims of sex trafficking in China.<ref> [https://weblog.iom.int/migrant-hero-michael-brosowski Migrant Hero: Michael Brosowski June 26, 2015] [[International Organization for Migration]] Retrieved May 26, 2016 </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{China topics}}\n{{Sex trafficking in East Asia|state=collapsed}}\n{{Sex trafficking|state=collapsed}}\n{{Prostitution in China}}\n{{Asia in topic|Sex trafficking in}}\n\n[[Category:Human trafficking in China]]\n[[Category:Human rights abuses in China]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:Forced marriage]]\n[[Category:Forced prostitution]]\n[[Category:Organized crime activity]]\n[[Category:Chinese women]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement in China]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China society]]\n[[Category:Prostitution in China]]\n[[Category:Sex industry]]\n[[Category:Rape in China]]\n[[Category:Sex trafficking by country|China]]\n[[Category:Social issues in China]]\n[[Category:Slavery in China]]\n[[Category:Crimes against women]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in China]]\n[[Category:Women in China]]\n", "text_old": "'''Sex trafficking in China''' is [[human trafficking]] for the purpose of [[Sexual slavery|sexual exploitation and slavery]] that occurs in the [[People's Republic of China]]. China, the world's most populous country, has one of the highest rates of human trafficking, including sex trafficking, in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailysignal.com/2014/11/20/nearly-two-thirds-human-trafficking-victims-asia/|title=Nearly Two-Thirds of Human Trafficking Victims Are from Asia|date=September 11, 2014|website=The Daily Signal}}</ref> It is a country of origin, destination, and transit for sexually trafficked persons.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://un-act.org/china/|title=China, The Trafficking Situation|website=United Nations Action for Cooperation Against Trafficking in Persons (UN-ACT)}}</ref> \n\nSex trafficking victims in the country are from all [[List of ethnic groups in China|ethnic groups in China]] and foreigners. [[Chinese people|Chinese citizens]], primarily women and girls, have been sex trafficked to the various [[provinces of China]], as well as other countries in [[Asia]] and different [[continents]]. They have been detected in [[overseas Chinese]] expatriate communities.<ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/2188327/florida-sex-spas-chinese-human-trafficking-rings|title=In Florida sex spas, Chinese human trafficking rings operated in plain sight|date=March 2, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1 /> China's internal migrant population, in the hundreds of millions, is particularly vulnerable to sex trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/reports/2018-trafficking-in-persons-report/china/|title=2018 Trafficking in Persons Report: China|website=United States Department of State}}</ref> Sex trafficked victims are forced into prostitution, marriages, and or pregnancies.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> They are threatened<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/cnainsider/vietnam-kidnapped-brides-trafficking-china-wives-11777162|title=Raped, beaten and sold in China: Vietnam's kidnapped young brides|date=August 3, 2019|website=Channel News Asia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-21/vietnam-sapa-women-trafficked-to-china/9675610|title=Vietnamese teen's escape from the China trafficking trade that sold her mother|date=September 18, 2018|website=ABC News}}</ref> and physically and psychologically harmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theaseanpost.com/article/myanmars-trafficked-brides|title=Myanmar\u2019s trafficked brides|date=March 31, 2019|website=The ASEAN Post}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2014/11/sex-trafficking-and-chinas-one-child-policy/|title=Sex Trafficking and China's One Child Policy|date=November 6, 2014|website=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/sold-raped-enslaved-human-trafficking-victims-shared-stories-in-2019-4030004.html|title=Sold, raped, enslaved: Human trafficking victims shared stories in 2019|date=December 24, 2019|website=VnExpress}}</ref> They contract [[sexually transmitted diseases]] from rapes, and abuse and starvation are common. Some women and girls are tortured<ref name=autogenerated14>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/oppressed-enslaved-brutalised-women-trafficked-north-korea-chinas/|title=Oppressed, enslaved and brutalised: The women trafficked from North Korea into China's sex trade|date=May 20, 2019|website=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated13>{{cite web|url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/vietnam-china-human-trafficking-growing-malady/|title=Vietnam-China human trafficking a growing malady|date=November 24, 2013|website=New Europe}}</ref> and or murdered.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/01/22/world/asia/china-sex-slaves-execution/index.html|title=China executes man who kept 6 women in dungeon as sex slaves|date=January 22, 2014|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-crime/chinese-man-sentenced-to-death-in-sex-slave-murder-case-idUSBRE8AT0CL20121130|title=Chinese man sentenced to death in sex slave murder case|date=November 30, 2012|website=Reuters}}</ref> \n\nSex trafficking and exploitation have permeated all levels of Chinese society. Male and female perpetrators in China come from a wide range of backgrounds and every social class. A number of traffickers are members of or facilitated by criminal organizations and gangs. Some government officials and workers, as well as foreigners, have profited from sex trafficking in China.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Rising incomes in China have spurred increased consumption of many services, both licit and illicit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/news/brief/colombia-china-sex-trafficking-network-uncovered/|title=Colombia to China Sex Trafficking Bust Illustrates Dynamics of Trade|date=August 25, 2017|website=InSight Crime}}</ref> It has occurred in businesses linked to [[Tourism in China|China's entertainment and tourism industries]]. Some reporters suggest that the [[Belt and Road Initiative]] and [[globalization]] have led to an increase in sex trafficking in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/3050632/bride-trafficking-hitch-chinas-belt-and-road|title=Bride trafficking, a problem on China's belt and road|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/south-asia/article/3041898/abused-raped-and-unfed-heart-wrenching-stories-pakistani|title=Abused, raped: heart-wrenching stories of Pakistani brides trafficked to China|date=December 13, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> Chinese sex traffickers operate throughout the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asia/thai-surrogate-chinese-arrested-illegal-surrogacy-raid-12432510|title=7 Thai surrogates, 2 Chinese nationals arrested in illegal surrogacy raid in Bangkok|date=February 13, 2020|website=CNA}}</ref>\nCybersex trafficking is a growing problem in twenty-first century China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/13/world/asia/north-korea-cybersex-china.html|title=After Fleeing North Korea, Women Get Trapped as Cybersex Slaves in China|date=September 13, 2019|website=The New York Times}}</ref> The global spread of high-speed internet and increase in computer, tablet, and smart phone ownership have fueled online or virtual forced prostitution and sex abuse and the creation of illegal pornographic videos purchased by users worldwide.\n\nThe scale of sex trafficking in China is difficult to know because of the lack of primary research and data collection, the clandestine nature of sex trafficking crimes, the fact that only a small minority of cases are reported to the authorities, and other factors.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Chinese government ministries as well as international and domestic agencies and organisations do some work to combat sex trafficking patterns, but this has not brought substantive improvements and responses have proved insufficient.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The enforcement of sex trafficking laws and investigating and prosecuting of trafficking cases have been immobilized by interagency collaboration and coordination challenges, logistical difficulties, poor border management,<ref name=autogenerated13 /> language barriers of foreign victims, political dynamics, corruption, and apathy.<ref name=autogenerated9>{{cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/interview/why-beijing-fails-fight-human-trafficking|title=Why Beijing Fails to Fight Human Trafficking|website=Council on Foreign Relations}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/trafficking-survivors-failed-world-190801143149035.html|title=Trafficking survivors are being failed the world over|website=Al Jazeera}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/10/chinas-bride-trafficking-problem/|title=China's Bride Trafficking Problem|date=October 30, 2019|website=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated18>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2019/05/16/North-Korea-women-in-China-trapped-in-sex-trade/7621557980738/|title=North Korea women in China trapped in sex trade|date=May 16, 2019|website=UPI}}</ref> Some Chinese police and officials, as well as overseas embassies and [[diplomatic missions]],<ref name=autogenerated17>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1236534/no-reply-from-chinese-embassy-on-pogo-sex-trade-hontiveros|title=No reply from Chinese Embassy on POGO sex trade \u2014 Hontiveros|date=March 4, 2019|website=Inquirer}}</ref> have been accused of negligence concerning counter-sex trafficking efforts and concern for victims.<ref name=autogenerated16>{{cite web|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2019/03/myanmar-chinas-bride-trafficking-problem/|title=Myanmar and China's Bride Trafficking Problem|date=March 22, 2019|website=Inter Press Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insightcrime.org/news/brief/colombia-china-sex-trafficking-network-uncovered/|title=Colombia to China Sex Trafficking Bust Illustrates Dynamics of Trade|date=August 25, 2017|website=InSight Crime}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/07/chinas-trafficked-brides/|title=China\u2019s Trafficked Brides|date=July 19, 2017|website=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Available statistics indicate that China needs to devote greater resources and implement better policies and strategies designed to reduce sex trafficking in the country.<ref name=autogenerated9 /> It is difficult for [[List of the largest trading partners of China|trading partners of China]] to criticize the country's inadequate anti-sex trafficking efforts because of fears of tensions.<ref name=autogenerated5 />  Chinese  civil society's efforts in countering sex trafficking are stymied by threats and coercion from criminal organizations and officials and the government's repression of women and human rights organizations, presses, and lawyers.<ref name=autogenerated9 /><ref name=autogenerated5 />  \n\n==Victims==\n[[File:China administrative.svg |upright=1.4|thumbnail|right|Chinese citizen and foreign victims are sex trafficked into and out of all [[provinces of China]]. They are raped and physically and psychologically harmed in other ways in homes, brothels, indirect sex establishments, and various business and work sites within these administrative divisions.]] \n\nVictims of sex trafficking for [[sexual slavery in China]] include, but are not limited to, children, impoverished, migrants, disabled persons, ethnic and religious minorities, foreigners, and overseas Chinese. It is not uncommon for victims of rape to be used additionally as forced laborers in homes, farms, and businesses.<ref name=autogenerated16 /> They, particularly forced prostitutes, often contract sexually transmitted diseases because the rapers do not wear condoms.<ref name=autogenerated13 /> Women and girls have contracted [[HIV]].<ref name=autogenerated19>{{cite web|url=https://www.gospelherald.com/articles/49719/20131127/compelled-by-love-the-church-in-china-fights-human-trafficking-part-ii.htm|title=Compelled by Love: The Church in China Fights Human Trafficking, Part II|date=November 27, 2013|website=The Gosepl Herald Society}}</ref> A number are verbally and physically abused and beaten,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caritas.org/2017/11/poverty-and-conflict-in-myanmar-fuel-human-trafficking/|title=POVERTY AND CONFLICT IN MYANMAR FUEL HUMAN TRAFFICKING|website=Caritas}}</ref> starved, drugged,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/04/17/asia/vietnamese-girls-child-brides-china/index.html|title=Vietnamese girls smuggled into China and sold as child brides|date=April 19, 2016|website=CNN World}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vietnaminsider.vn/vietnamese-trafficking-victims-shared-their-stories/|title=Vietnamese trafficking victims shared their stories|date=December 25, 2019|website=Vietnam Insider}}</ref> and sexually tortured.<ref name=autogenerated13 /><ref name=autogenerated14 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/vietnamese-trafficking-victim-reveals-heartbreaking-ordeal|title=Vietnamese Trafficking Victim Reveals Heartbreaking Ordeal|date=September 24, 2015|website=VOA News}}</ref> Many sex trafficked women and girls are never found.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n  \nSurviving victims face ostracization from their families and communities.<ref name=autogenerated12>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5555695/china-women-trafficking-myanmar/|title=A Shortage of Women in China Has Led to the Trafficking of 'Brides' From Myanmar, Says a Report|date=March 21, 2019|website=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Some victims are discouraged by family and friends from seeking justice. Some, suffering from trauma or forced drug addiction because of their captors and in extreme poverty, reluctantly return to prostitution after being rescued.<ref name=autogenerated19 /> Many mothers who fled or were rescued will never be able to see their children held by the buying family or sold by the traffickers.<ref name=autogenerated1a>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/oppressed-enslaved-brutalised-women-trafficked-north-korea-chinas/|title=Oppressed, enslaved and brutalised: The women trafficked from North Korea into China's sex trade|date=May 20, 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph|last1=Smith|first1=Nicola|last2=Farmer|first2=Ben}}</ref> \nSome former trafficking victims are reluctant to report traffickers to the local authorities because they fear reprisal from criminals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/11/vietnams-human-trafficking-problem-is-too-big-to-ignore/|title=Vietnam's Human Trafficking Problem Is Too Big to Ignore|date=November 8, 2019|website=The Diplomat}}</ref>  \nSome recused victims get abducted and sex trafficked again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/thousands-of-myanmar-women-forced-into-marriages-in-china/a-46625465|title=Thousands of Myanmar women forced into marriages in China|date=July 12, 2018|website=DW News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/21/interview-why-brides-myanmar-are-trafficked-china#|title=Interview: Why \u2018Brides\u2019 From Myanmar Are Trafficked to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\nTrafficking survivors may need urgent medical care for problems ranging from injuries due to abuse to sexual and reproductive health needs. They need shelter as sometimes they cannot return to families that were complicit in their trafficking. They need legal assistance to ensure that the justice system - which too often lets trafficking victims down - is responsive to their needs for accountability and compensation. Many need financial assistance as months and years of sexual slavery resulted in no education and income.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/08/05/trafficking-survivors-are-being-failed-world-over#|title=Trafficking Survivors Are Being Failed the World Over|date=August 5, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese government's protection of victims has been criticized. Chinese law enforcement officials have arrested and detained foreign women on suspicion of prostitution crimes without screening them for indicators of sexual exploitation\u2014sometimes for as long as four months\u2014before deporting them for immigration violations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /> The police have treated the women and girls as violators of immigration law but have taken little action against the their traffickers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/thousands-of-myanmar-women-forced-into-marriages-in-china/a-46625465|title=Thousands of Myanmar women forced into marriages in China|date=July 12, 2018|website=DW News}}</ref>  \n\nThere is a need for a greater rehabilitative assistance and protection services, including comprehensive counseling and medical reintegration of the victims.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Detained or imprisoned women have beaten by other inmates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/oppressed-enslaved-brutalised-women-trafficked-north-korea-chinas/|title=Oppressed, enslaved and brutalised: The women trafficked from North Korea into China's sex trade|date=May 20, 2019|newspaper=The Telegraph|last1=Smith|first1=Nicola|last2=Farmer|first2=Ben}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese government maintains a wide network of shelters across the country, providing food, accommodation and other services to Chinese citizens facing various kinds of challenges. The system, however, is inexperienced in supporting foreigners in need of help. Anecdotal evidence suggests that foreigner women escaping conditions of forced marriage, some pregnant, are at times not granted access to shelters and their services. Specialist support services exist for children, including specialized shelters. Emergency shelters, physical and mental health services, education, job training, financial assistance, and family reunification are available for all groups.<ref name=autogenerated7>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalslaveryindex.org/2018/findings/highlights/|title=China Country Data|website=Global Slavery Index}}</ref> \n\n===Females===\nFemales are more vulnerable than males because of entrenched misogyny that causes men to inferiorize and commoditize women and girls.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> Traditional patriarchal structures reinforce gender inequality, especially in rural areas where females are oftentimes not afforded the same opportunities as males and are forced to submit to male authority. This inequality leaves women and girls increasingly marginalized and vulnerable to sex trafficking. \n\nThe [[one-child policy]] and preference for sons over daughters has led to a skewed sex ratio in which men outnumber women in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref> Consequently, there is an increase demand for trafficked prostitutes and wives in China. \n<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n   \n===Children===\nChildren have been targeted by perpetrators.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2017/07/chinas-trafficked-brides/|title=China\u2019s Trafficked Brides|date=July 19, 2017|website=The Diplomat}}</ref> Those from rural areas and migrant students, as well as [[Left-behind children in China|left-behind children]] whose parents have migrated to the cities and other countries, have been identified as a vulnerable population to sex trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=https://www.ecpat.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/3.-SECTT-CHINA.pdf|title=Global Study on Sexual Exploitation of Children in Travel and Tourism. Country-specific Report, China.|date=2015|website=ECPAT International}}</ref> Children who are [[Adoption fraud|illegal adopted]] are vulnerable to sexual exploitation.\n\n===People in poverty===\nSex traffickers in China often abduct or purchase women and girls from families in poverty or facing financial crisis, particularly the rural poor, because the victims often do not have any political power and connections and lack education about sex trafficking laws, which enables the captors to not attract much attention or publicity.<ref name=autogenerated16 />\n\n===Migrants===\nThe [[hukou]] household registration system in China has contributed to the vulnerability of internal migrants by limiting employment opportunities and reducing access to social services, particularly for Chinese victims returning from exploitation abroad.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Disabled persons===\nDisabled persons, including those with mental illness or who are deaf and mute, have been trafficked into and out of China by perpetrators.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Traffickers target adults and children with disabilities whose parents have left them with relatives to migrate to the cities.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Ethnic and religious minorities===\nWomen and girls from minority groups are at an increased risk of sex trafficking because population displacements and a lack of political representation, power, and protection.<ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref>\n\n===Foreigners===\nForeign women and girls from [[Mongolia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/mongolias-prostitution-zones-women-trade-sex-fuel-sub-zero-temperatures/|title=Mongolia's prostitution zones, where women trade sex for fuel in sub-zero temperatures|date=February 19, 2019|website=The Telegraph}}</ref> [[Vietnam]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/sold-raped-enslaved-human-trafficking-victims-shared-stories-in-2019-4030004.html|title=Sold, raped, enslaved: Human trafficking victims shared stories in 2019|date=December 24, 2019|website=VnExpress International}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated13 /> [[Cambodia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/106505/woman-accused-human-trafficking/|title=Woman accused of human trafficking|date=February 5, 2018|website=Khmer Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khmertimeskh.com/64043/poverty-causes-trafficking-to-china-says-report/|title=Poverty Causes Trafficking to China, Says Report|date=September 1, 2016|website=Khmer Times}}</ref> [[Myanmar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/geopolitics/article/2176841/after-fleeing-violence-home-myanmese-women-face-forced|title=In China, thousands of Myanmar women are forced into childbirth|date=December 7, 2018|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> [[Thailand]], [[Malaysia]], [[Laos]], the [[Philippines]], [[Indonesia]], and other countries have been trafficked into China for sexual exploitation.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=https://www.cecc.gov/sites/chinacommission.house.gov/files/documents/CECC_ExecutiveSummary2019_FINAL_0.pdf|title=Congressional-Executive Commission on China 2019 Annual Report\u2014Executive Summary|website=Congressional-Executive Commission on China}}</ref> They experience difficulties being rescued because they do not speak Chinese and have no identification documents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3015603/chinese-police-free-more-1100-human-trafficking-victims-after|title=Chinese police free more than 1,100 human trafficking victims after targeting Southeast Asian networks|date=June 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> \n\nAuthorities continue to detain and deport [[North Korea]] sexually trafficked victims who may face severe punishment and/or death upon their repatriation.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The majority of North Korean refugees leaving the DPRK are women. The Chinese government's refusal to recognize these women as refugees denies them legal protection and may encourage the trafficking of North Korean women and girls within China. Many children born to Chinese fathers and North Korean mothers remain deprived of basic rights to education and other public services, owing to their lack of legal resident status in China, which constitute violations of the PRC Nationality Law and the Convention on the Rights of the Child.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\n===Overseas Chinese===\nChinese women and girls are subjected to sex trafficking in countries throughout the world. Some are deceived into prostitution or confined to private homes where they are raped.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nMany Chinese victims sex trafficked into the [[United States]] are forced to work in brothels disguised as [[massage parlors]]. The conditions in these illegal establishments are sometimes appalling. Money collected by operators is transferred to superiors in China at times.<ref name=autogenerated6 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/20191214/orchids-of-asia-case-425k-in-cash-lots-in-100-bills-seized-by-police|title=Orchids of Asia case: $425K in cash, lots in $100 bills, seized by police|date=December 14, 2019|website=The Palm Beach Post}}</ref> \n\nChinese women and girls have been sex trafficked to cater to men involved with or working for [[Philippine Offshore Gaming Operators]].<ref name=autogenerated17 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/1817631|title=\u2018Probe Chinese group\u2019s sex trafficking activities\u2019|date=August 6, 2019|website=SunStar Cebu}}</ref>\n\nChinese victims have been sex trafficked to businesses catering to people seeing the [[Southeast Asian Games]] and other sports events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/lifestyle-culture/article/3041328/sea-games-foreign-tourist-surge-philippines-sees-rising|title=SEA Games: foreign tourist surge to Philippines sees rising risk of sex trafficking|date=December 10, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\n==Forced prostitution==\n[[File:Barber shop Bao'an Shenzhen China.jpg|300px|thumbnail|right|Chinese and foreign women and girls sex trafficked and forced into prostitution are raped in brothels and establishments similar to this one in [[South China]]. 'Online rape dens' in more inconspicuous premises are increasingly being used for digital and live pornographic video sharing in the twenty-first century.]]\n\nVictims are coerced by perpetrators by imposing large travel fees, confiscating passports,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caritas.org/2017/11/poverty-and-conflict-in-myanmar-fuel-human-trafficking/|title=POVERTY AND CONFLICT IN MYANMAR FUEL HUMAN TRAFFICKING|website=Caritas}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-vietnam-humantrafficking/trafficking-of-vietnamese-women-for-sex-and-marriage-expands-across-region-expert-idUSKCN0Y9180|title=Trafficking of Vietnamese women for sex and marriage expands across region: expert|date=May 18, 2016|website=Reuters}}</ref> confining victims, or are physically and financially threatened to compel their engagement in commercial sex.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Victims are deceived by traffickers and brothel operators by answering ads for jobs as waitresses, servers, cleaners, and more.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Some have been told they could study in universities and educational institutions at low costs only to be sold into prostitution.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Some are drugged<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/04/17/asia/vietnamese-girls-child-brides-china/index.html|title=Vietnamese girls smuggled into China and sold as child brides|date=April 19, 2016|website=CNN World}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/vietnamese-woman-trafficked-to-china-returns-home-after-22-years-3947636.html|title=Vietnamese woman trafficked to China returns home after 22 years|date=July 4, 2019|website=VnExpress}}</ref>   and abducted.<ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/sold-raped-enslaved-human-trafficking-victims-shared-stories-in-2019-4030004.html|title=Sold, raped, enslaved: Human trafficking victims shared stories in 2019|date=December 24, 2019|website=VnExpress}}</ref> The brothels are often indirect sex establishments, such as beer gardens, massage parlors, salons, karaoke bars, retail spaces, and non-commercial sites.<ref name=autogenerated8>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3006909/non-profit-group-which-helps-sex-trafficking-victims-seeks|title=Non-profit group, which helps sex-trafficking victims, seeks tie-ups with ethical business partners in Hong Kong|date=April 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref> Other locations include construction sites, remote mining and logging camps, and areas with high concentrations of Chinese migrant workers.<ref name=autogenerated14 /> \n\nWomen and girls who are trafficked into brothels are raped by hundreds of men.<ref name=autogenerated8 /> They are kept under strict surveillance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/vietnamese-trafficking-victim-reveals-heartbreaking-ordeal|title=Vietnamese Trafficking Victim Reveals Heartbreaking Ordeal|date=September 24, 2015|website=VOA News}}</ref> It is not uncommon for them to be guarded and tied or locked up and never allowed to go outside.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/sold-raped-enslaved-human-trafficking-victims-shared-stories-in-2019-4030004.html|title=Sold, raped, enslaved: Human trafficking victims shared stories in 2019|date=December 24, 2019|website=VnExpress}}</ref> Some are beaten and or contract sexually transmitted diseases. Others commit suicide.<ref name=autogenerated15>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/society/article/2151075/vietnam-without-love-child-brides-china|title=From Vietnam, without love: the child brides of China|date=June 17, 2018|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nThere are more males than females in China because of the one-child policy and preference. This may have led to an increase in the demand for prostitution.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> China's business culture also involves frequenting entertainment venues, some which have forced prostitutes.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n===Online rape dens===\nA number of sexually trafficked victims in China are habitually subjected to penetrative vaginal and anal rape, groping, and forced masturbation  live on camera in 'online rape dens.'<ref name=autogenerated18 /><ref name=autogenerated14 /> Gang rape occurs in these dens as well. Traffickers sell these videos and earn revenue by adding them to [[pornography]] websites.\n\n==Forced marriages and pregnancies==\nIllicit brokers increasingly facilitate the forced and fraudulent marriage, or bride trafficking, of Chinese women and foreigners to men in China and from abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/10/31/chinas-bride-trafficking-problem#|title=China's Bride Trafficking Problem|date=October 31, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /> These women are sexually exploited in the illegal marriages. The Chinese government's birth limitation policy and the cultural preference for sons have resulted in an uneven sex ratio, contributing substantially to the demand for brides from rural areas and outside of China.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nSome female trafficking victims are raped so they become surrogate mothers and bear children.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> There are testimonies that women and girls have also been injected with sperm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2019/7/compilation-trafficking-survivors-share-stories|title=Trafficked: Three survivors of human trafficking share their stories|date=July 29, 2019|website=UN Women}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Women,-children-and-babies:-human-trafficking-to-China-is-on-the-rise-47513.html|title=Women, children and babies: human trafficking to China is on the rise|date=July 11, 2019|website=Asia News}}</ref> Their children are kept by the captors, the paying husband, or sold to other families.<ref name=autogenerated12 /> Some husbands let other men, including his relatives, rape his trafficked wife.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/ad6b5fb667ca449d8cadc05bb2bc0a41|title=Pakistani police target traffickers selling brides to China|date=June 17, 2019|website=AP News}}</ref> Some women and girls who have been trafficked to entire families of men, who are poor and pool their money together to buy one wife.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vietcetera.com/en/pacific-links-foundation-the-battle-against-human-trafficking/|title=Pacific Links Foundation: The Battle Against Human Trafficking|date=August 7, 2017|website=Vietcetera}}</ref>  \n\n==Industries==\n\n===Entertainment and tourism industries===\nChina's [[Tourism in China|entertainment and tourism industries]] have developed rapidly with the country's economic growth. Victims are trafficked into businesses, including restaurants, bars, casinos, and nightclubs, linked to these industries.<ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.china.org.cn/opinion/2014-02/20/content_31532335.htm|title=Earnest bid to end sex trade|date=February 20, 2014|website=China Org}}</ref>\n\n===Mining industry===\nWomen and girls are trafficked to mining sector sites.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/mongolias-prostitution-zones-women-trade-sex-fuel-sub-zero-temperatures/|title=Mongolia's prostitution zones, where women trade sex for fuel in sub-zero temperatures|date=February 19, 2019|website=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Special administrative regions of China==\nChinese [[Mainland Chinese|mainlanders]] are sex trafficked into the [[special administrative regions of China]]. Women and girls within these administrative regions are also trafficked to other parts of the city or to mainland cities.    \n\n===Hong Kong===\n{{Main|Sex trafficking in Hong Kong}}\n\nMainland Chinese women and girls are [[Sex trafficking in Hong Kong|sex trafficked into Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Making-a-difference/Change-Agent/2015/1022/New-ways-to-help-Hong-Kong-s-human-trafficking-victims|title=New ways to help Hong Kong's human trafficking victims|date=October 22, 2015|website=CN Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/article/1901109/human-trafficking-hong-kong-hidden-plain-sight|title=Human trafficking in Hong Kong: hidden in plain sight|date=January 16, 2016|website=South China Morning Post Magazine}}</ref> They are forced into prostitution in brothels, homes, and businesses in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Making-a-difference/Change-Agent/2015/1022/New-ways-to-help-Hong-Kong-s-human-trafficking-victims|title=New ways to help Hong Kong's human trafficking victims|date=October 22, 2015|website=CN Monitor}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/article/1901109/human-trafficking-hong-kong-hidden-plain-sight|title=Human trafficking in Hong Kong: hidden in plain sight|date=January 16, 2016|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-crime/article/2134591/fed-human-trafficking-hong-kong-migrant-workers-hold-vigil|title=Fed up with human trafficking, Hong Kong migrant workers hold vigil demanding justice|date=February 25, 2018|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1986535/hong-kong-must-lead-fight-against-human-trafficking-rather|title=Hong Kong must lead the fight against human trafficking, rather than just do the bare minimum|date=July 8, 2016|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Global Slavery Index]], the [[Hong Kong]] Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China has a 'weak response' to modern slavery, including sexual slavery, relative to [[gross domestic product]] based on [[purchasing power parity]].<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\n===Macau===\n{{Main|Sex trafficking in Macau}}\nMainland Chinese victims are [[Sex trafficking in Hong Kong|sex trafficked into Macau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.macaubusiness.com/macaus-ranking-upgraded-in-us-human-trafficking-report-govt-dismisses-untrue-conclusions/|title=Macau\u2019s ranking upgraded in US human trafficking report, Gov\u2019t dismisses \u2018untrue\u2019 conclusions|date=June 21, 2019|website=Macau Business}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.plataformamedia.com/en-uk/news/society/human-trafficking-is-still-a-big-problem-in-macau-hong-kong-newspaper-says-11428089.html|title=Human trafficking is still a big problem in Macau, Hong Kong newspaper says|date=October 21, 2019|website=Plataforma}}</ref> They are sex slaves in brothels and hotel rooms near the casinos and other entertainment venues. \n\n==China\u2013Mongolia border==\n{{See also|Sex trafficking in Mongolia}}\n\nMongolian and Chinese women and girls are sex trafficked to and through the [[China\u2013Mongolia border]] border.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2009-07-22/stolen-mongolia-sex|title=Stolen from Mongolia for sex|date=July 22, 2009|website=PRI}}</ref> At the border and in the [[Gobi Desert]] are global mining sector and other heavy industry operations with large workforces of isolated men. These, including the ones in [[Tavan Tolgoi|Tavan Tolgoi coal deposits]]  have been a focal point for prostitution and sex trafficking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/women-and-girls/mongolias-prostitution-zones-women-trade-sex-fuel-sub-zero-temperatures/|title=Mongolia's prostitution zones, where women trade sex for fuel in sub-zero temperatures|date=February 19, 2019|website=The Telegraph}}</ref> \n\n==Criminal organizations and perpetrators==\nDomestic and transnational criminal organizations operating in China are becoming more organized, professional, and diverse. Members of criminal organizations use fraudulent employment offers, threats, direct force, and kidnapping to trafficked victims into sexual exploitation and slavery. Some marriage brokers, matchmakers, mail-order bride service managers,  and loan sharks obtain women for criminal organizations.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Traffickers frequently take advantage of [[debt bondage]] to control their victims. They also threaten families back home to ensure the victims continue to cooperate. <ref name=autogenerated11>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2019/11/vietnams-human-trafficking-problem-is-too-big-to-ignore/|title=Vietnam's Human Trafficking Problem Is Too Big to Ignore|date=November 8, 2019|website=The Diplomat}}</ref> \n\nChinese government officials and businessmen, facilitated by criminal organizations, have been arrested for participating in forcible commercial sexual exploitation.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> There are government officials who facilitate or are complicit in sex trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated2 /><ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nFemales perpetrators are sometimes victims of trafficking themselves and are coerced to abduct more women and girls for their captors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.irrawaddy.com/article.php?art_id=21486|title=A Grim Trade: Trafficking Palaung Women to China|date=June 14, 2011|website=The Irrawaddy}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref> Female traffickers can better conceal their identities to the police and win trust from victims more easily compared with their male counterparts.<ref name=autogenerated13 />\n\nFamily members, relatives, friends, classmates, colleagues, or acquaintances sometimes sell girls to sex traffickers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/report/2019/03/21/give-us-baby-and-well-let-you-go/trafficking-kachin-brides-myanmar-china|title=Give Us a Baby and We\u2019ll Let You Go: Trafficking of Kachin Brides from Myanmar to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated16 /><ref name=autogenerated15 />\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://qz.com/525900/child-trafficking-in-china-often-starts-with-parents-selling-their-own-kids/|title=Child trafficking in China often starts with parents selling their own kids|date=October 16, 2015|website=Quartz}}</ref> The girls' parents or the trafficker may take her to the hospital to get a [[virginity test]].<ref name=autogenerated8 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/21/interview-why-brides-myanmar-are-trafficked-china#|title=Interview: Why \u2018Brides\u2019 From Myanmar Are Trafficked to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/world/region/2020/01/554485/1807-human-trafficking-victims-rescued-thailand-2019|title=1,807 human trafficking victims rescued in Thailand in 2019|date=January 8, 2020|website=New Straits Times}}</ref>\n\nSome sex traffickers impersonate police officers to gain victims' trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/80-percent-of-vietnamese-human-trafficking-victims-end-up-in-china-3960605.html|title=80 percent of Vietnamese human trafficking victims end up in China|date=August 1, 2019|website=VnExpress International}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref> \n\nPerpetrators are motivated by monetary incentives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vietcetera.com/en/pacific-links-foundation-the-battle-against-human-trafficking/|title=Pacific Links Foundation: The Battle Against Human Trafficking|date=August 7, 2017|website=Vietcetera}}</ref> \n\n===Online deception===\nPerpetrators in China use the internet, gaming sites, social media, [[WeChat]], [[Telegram]], and other messaging apps to lure victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2020/03/01/washington-county-charges-offer-glimpse-into-the-secret-world-of-chinese-sex-trafficking/|title=Washington County charges offer glimpse into the secret world of Chinese sex trafficking|date=March 1, 2020|website=Twin Cities Pioneer Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewhumanitarian.org/news/2016/09/02/vietnam-wakes-its-human-trafficking-problem|title=Vietnam wakes up to its human trafficking problem|date=September 2, 2016|website=The New Humanitarian}}</ref> Male traffickers often entice females with phony online dating relationships and persuade them to move to a different province or abroad, then subject them to sexual slavery.<ref name=autogenerated11 /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/china-is-main-destination-for-vietnamese-trafficking-victims-official-3797546.html|title=China is main destination for Vietnamese trafficking victims: official|date=August 24, 2018|website=VnExpress}}</ref>    \n\n==Unreported crimes==\nA criminologist in the [[People's Public Security University of China]], stated, \u201cbehind\nevery reported sex abuse case, there might be six hidden cases unreported\u201d.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Victims might be fearful and or ashamed to report a sex crime. Children and mentally disabled persons might not be even aware that such illegal acts has been committed against them.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Some brothels with sex trafficked victims operate underground.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Data collection of sex trafficking crimes in China have been flawed which has led to incidents not being reported.\n\n==Legal framework==\nVictims were legally entitled to request criminal prosecution and claim financial restitution through civil lawsuits against their traffickers.<ref name=autogenerated7 /> \n\nChina has not signed, ratified, acceded to the Convention to Suppress the Slave Trade and Slavery or [[Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery]]. It has for the [[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, Especially Women and Children]], [[Optional Protocol on the Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography]]\n \nArticle 240 of the [[Chinese law|Chinese Criminal Code]] criminalized the \u201cabducting and trafficking of women or children.\u201d Article 244 criminalized the forcing of a person \u201cto work by violence, threat or restriction of personal freedom\u201d and recruiting, transporting, or otherwise assisting in forcing others to labor. Article 358 criminalized forced prostitution. Under the provisions of article 296 of the Criminal Code, a person who enslaves another or places him in a position without freedom, similar to slavery, shall be punished with imprisonment for not less than one and not more than seven years. Article 359 criminalized harboring prostitution or seducing or introducing others into prostitution.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nThe Chinese government maintained insufficient law enforcement efforts of sex trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> It has been recommended that China vigorously investigate, prosecute, and impose prison sentences on perpetrators of sex trafficking; update the legal framework concerning the criminzaliztion of sex trafficking, including the facilitation of prostitution involving children younger than the age of 18; expand efforts to institute proactive, formal procedures to systematically identify trafficking victims throughout the country; train front-line officers on their implementation; cease penalization of victims for acts committed as a direct result of being subjected to sex trafficking; ensure authorities do not subject trafficking victims to detention, punishment, or forcible repatriation; increase the transparency of government efforts to combat trafficking and provide disaggregated data on investigations and prosecutions, victim identification, and service provision, including by continuing to share relevant data with international partners.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n==Anti-sex trafficking mechanisms==\nChina has a \u201cNational Plan of Action on Combating Trafficking in Women and Children.\u201d The Ministry of Public Security, Ministry of Civil Affairs, Supreme People's Court, and All China Women's Federation have issued various joint policies on prosecution, prevention and victim protection. The Inter-Ministerial Joint Meeting Mechanism (IMJMM) holds annual and thematic meetings as well as information sharing on a monthly basis. Anti-sex trafficking campaigns have been disseminated through television, print media and online platforms. Numerous documentaries and animations have been produced and broadcast to raise awareness among the general public.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nCoordinated Mekong Ministerial Initiative against Trafficking (COMMIT) Task Force (2005), with UN-ACT as secretariat. Chinese law enforcement carries out hotspot policing conducted in high risk areas and joint border operations conducted with law enforcement counterparts in Vietnam and Myanmar. A team of interpreters for Greater Mekong Sub-region (GMS) languages has been established to support cross-border case investigations.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAn \u201cOperational Guide for Anti-Trafficking Police\u201d has been established and is currently used by police officers.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nSeveral projects have been initiated by the All China Women's Federation (ACWF) to prevent trafficking among migrant populations in various source and destination provinces.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nShelters provide interim care to trafficking victims with managers and staff in most provinces having received training (Ministry of Civil Affairs). An operational guide to assist victims of trafficking has been developed and distributed to all shelters.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===Official and police training=== \nTraining for police, teachers, social workers, labor inspectors, immigration officials, shelter managers, marriage registration officials, and other government workers has taken place on basic legal frameworks surrounding sexual slavery and victim identification. In conjunction with an international organisation, authorities sponsored and participated in trainings on victim identification and assistance for consular officials and law enforcement, regulation of marriage migration, and interagency implementation of the national referral mechanism. The Ministry of Public Security promulgated written instructions to law enforcement officers throughout the country with the aim of clarifying procedures for identifying victims among individuals in prostitution and those who may be subjected to exploitation via forced or fraudulent marriage. The government reported funding training in rural areas for court officials and prosecutors; however, it did not provide detailed information on these efforts. In addition, law enforcement officials, prosecutors, and judges attended trainings on trafficking organized by other countries and international organizations; when authorities participated in these trainings, the PRC sometimes provided speakers and venues, and funded lodging, transportation, and meals for some participants.The office to combat trafficking in persons developed and approved trafficking victim identification procedures and disseminated them to law enforcement officials throughout the country. The government acknowledged that victim identification procedures varied according to local officials' training and understanding of trafficking; this variation increased the risk that unidentified trafficking victims were detained and deported following arrest for unlawful acts committed as a direct result of being subjected to human trafficking.<ref name=autogenerated7 />\n\n===Public education===\nPublic education about sex crimes in China exists but is insufficient. Many Chinese children receive little information about sexual offences and have a weak awareness or capability to protect themselves from such offences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ecpat.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/3.-SECTT-CHINA.pdf|title=Global Study on Sexual Exploitation of Children in Travel and Tourism. Country-specific Report, China.|date=2015|website=ECPAT Intercriminalovernational}}</ref>\n\nChina's highest-rated television channel ran broadcasts raising awareness on trafficking. The government  disseminates some anti-trafficking messages in train and bus stations and through media such as cell phones, television, and the internet. Through China's social media platforms, such as [[Sina Weibo]], the Ministry of Public Security reported using its official microblog to raise awareness of trafficking and receive information from the public regarding suspected trafficking cases. In 2018, the Ministry of Public Security reportedly sent 350,000 police officers to public schools to educate children about the risks of exploitation. Article highlights announcement of rescued children on Weibo, a popular Chinese microblogging platform, accompanied by photos of them. At the end of the article, tips and reminders are provided for readers on what to do if they suspect any instance of child trafficking or abduction. A link is also provided to the National Abduction and Family Search Platform, which acts as a directory for abducted and trafficked children.<ref name=autogenerated10>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalslaveryindex.org/2019/data/country-data/china/|title=China Country Data|date=2019|website=Global Slavery Index}}</ref>\n\nThe two Women's Federations and the Publicity Department focus on raising awareness and provide assistance with victim support. They run annual campaigns that focus on school curricula, television ads and transportation hubs, especially around the time of the Spring Festival. \n\n===Reporting===\nGovernment websites provide list of relevant agencies and departments and their hotlines. Several of the most popular apps in China have the additional function of helping locate missing persons through localized push notifications. Scores of specialist apps for registering family members young and old or reporting suspected child trafficking have also been appearing in the country's app stores. The free, 24/7 dial 110 nationwide police calling system allows victims or witnesses to obtain assistance from the police.<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n==Government response problems==\nAccording to [[Human Rights Watch]], Chinese law enforcement officers in certain jurisdictions make little effort to save sex trafficking victims.<ref name=autogenerated12 />\n\nThere has been not been an increase in public reports of sexual slavery cases in recent years. The Ministry of Public Security has not reported the number of investigations initiated into possible trafficking cases.<ref name=autogenerated10 /> \n\nThe reporting mechanisms (websites, hotline, etc.) do operate in multiple languages.<ref name=autogenerated10 />  \n\nTraining for first responders of trafficking crimes is not delivered systematically and at regular intervals. Reports suggest that screening procedures exist but it is unclear if these have been distributed to all first res ponders or concern both victim screening and identification.\n<ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n==Corruption== \nSome government officials and police have been complicit in sex trafficking. Some police have demanded bribes in order to return victims to their families.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/thousands-of-myanmar-women-forced-into-marriages-in-china/a-46625465|title=Thousands of Myanmar women forced into marriages in China|date=July 12, 2018|website=DW News}}</ref>\n\n==Government human rights violations==\n{{Main|Human rights in China}}\nThe Chinese government's human rights violations have hampered anti-sex trafficking initiatives.<ref name=autogenerated9 /> Sustained attacks on organizations and lawyers have resulted in victims not being able to seek justice.<ref name=autogenerated5 />\n\n==Anti-trafficking Organizations==\nThere are civil society organizations working to rescue women, but these organizations have limited resources.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/21/interview-why-brides-myanmar-are-trafficked-china#|title=Interview: Why \u2018Brides\u2019 From Myanmar Are Trafficked to China|date=March 21, 2019|website=Human Rights Watch}}</ref>\n\nChristian organizations save sex trafficked victims in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asianews.it/news-en/Vietnams-modern-sex-slaves-sold-in-China-as-prostitutes-or-brides-33361.html|title=Vietnam's \"modern sex slaves\" sold in China as prostitutes or brides|date=February 3, 2015|website=Asia News}}</ref>\n\n[[Agape International Missions]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/southeast-asia/article/3006909/non-profit-group-which-helps-sex-trafficking-victims-seeks|title=Non-profit group, which helps sex-trafficking victims, seeks tie-ups with ethical business partners in Hong Kong|date=April 21, 2019|website=South China Morning Post}}</ref> and [[Blue Dragon Children's Foundation]] save victims of sex trafficking in China.<ref> [https://weblog.iom.int/migrant-hero-michael-brosowski Migrant Hero: Michael Brosowski June 26, 2015] [[International Organization for Migration]] Retrieved May 26, 2016 </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{China topics}}\n{{Sex trafficking in East Asia|state=collapsed}}\n{{Sex trafficking|state=collapsed}}\n{{Prostitution in China}}\n{{Asia in topic|Sex trafficking in}}\n\n[[Category:Human trafficking in China]]\n[[Category:Human rights abuses in China]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:Forced marriage]]\n[[Category:Forced prostitution]]\n[[Category:Organized crime activity]]\n[[Category:Chinese women]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement in China]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China society]]\n[[Category:Prostitution in China]]\n[[Category:Sex industry]]\n[[Category:Rape in China]]\n[[Category:Sex trafficking by country|China]]\n[[Category:Social issues in China]]\n[[Category:Slavery in China]]\n[[Category:Crimes against women]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in China]]\n[[Category:Women in China]]\n", "name_user": "Wikipedianuhai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChina\u2013Mongolia border", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sex_trafficking_in_China"}
{"title_page": "Mark Lee (singer)", "text_new": "{{unreliable sources|date=June 2019}}\n{{short description|Canadian-Korean rapper}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Lee \n| birth_name         = Mark Lee\n| native_name        = \uc774\ub9c8\ud06c\n| image              = 181012 Mark KBS '\ubba4\uc9c1\ubc45\ud06c' \ub9ac\ud5c8\uc124 \ucd9c\uadfc\uae38 \uc9c1\ucea0 \uc601\uc0c1.png\n| caption            = Mark Lee in October 2018\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1999|8|2}}\n| birth_place        = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality        = Canadian\n| other_names        = Lee Min-hyung\n| education          = [[School of Performing Arts Seoul]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[hip-hop]]}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[SM Entertainment|SM]]|[[Avex Trax]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[NCT (band)|NCT]]|[[NCT 127]]|[[NCT U]]|[[NCT Dream]]|[[SuperM]]|[[SM Rookies]]|[[SM Town]]}}\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| title           = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul          = \uc774\ubbfc\ud615\n| hanja           = {{linktext|\u674e|\u654f|\u4ea8}}\n| rr              = I Minhyeong\n| mr              = Yi Minhy\u014fng\n| hangulstage     = \ub9c8\ud06c\n| rrstage         = Ma Keu\n| mrstage         = Ma K'\u016d\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Lee''' (born August 2, 1999), known professionally as '''Mark''', is a Canadian rapper and singer-songwriter based in South Korea. He is best known as a member of the South Korean boy group [[NCT (band)|NCT]] and its sub-units NCT U, [[NCT 127]], and [[NCT Dream]]. Mark made his debut in April 2016 as a member of rotational unit NCT U, became a member of Seoul-based fixed unit NCT 127 in July 2016 and also a member of NCT Dream in August 2016. In October 2019, Mark debuted as a member of the supergroup [[SuperM]].\n\n==Career==\n===2013\u20132015: SM Rookies===\nIn 2012, Mark joined [[SM Entertainment]] after passing the SM Global Audition in Canada in 2010.\n\nIn December 2013, Mark was introduced as a member of [[SM Rookies]], a pre-debut training team managed by SM Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=201312171039311138|title='SM\ub8e8\ud0a4\uc988' \ub9c8\ud06c\u00b7\uc9c0\uc131\u00b7\ud55c\uc194 \uc804\uaca9\uacf5\uac1c, \uc548\ubb34\uac00 \ud1a0\ub2c8\ud14c\uc2a4\ud0c0 \uadf9\ucc2c|last=Jeon|first=Won|date=December 13, 2013|publisher=MyDaily|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Mark appeared on [[Exo 90:2014]], a reality TV Show starring [[Exo (band)|Exo]], alongside other members of the SM Rookies program, where they performed songs and recreated music videos of prominent 90s [[K-pop]] idols.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.osen.co.kr/article/G1109972619|title=[\uc5b4\uc800\uaed8TV] \u2018\uc5d1\uc18c902014\u2019 K\ud31d \uc2dc\ud5d8, 90 \ubc18\uac11\uace0 2014 \uc0c8\ub86d\uace0|last=Kim|first=Sara|date=October 4, 2014|publisher=Osen|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Mark appeared on [[Disney Channel Korea]]'s ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club]]'' as a Mouseketeer alongside other members of the SM Rookies program, some of which are currently in [[NCT Dream]]. The show aired from July 23 to December 17, 2015 and was hosted by [[Leeteuk]] of [[Super Junior]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=743716|title=\ub514\uc988\ub2c8\ucc44\ub110, \ud55c\uad6d\ud310 \u2018\ubbf8\ud0a4\ub9c8\uc6b0\uc2a4\ud074\ub7fd\u2019 \uc81c\uc791 \u2018SM \ub8e8\ud0a4\uc988 \ucd9c\uc5f0\u2019|last=Hwang|first=Geung-ji|date=July 9, 2015|publisher=TV Report|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: NCT and solo endeavors===\nIn April 2016, SM Entertainment confirmed Mark alongside five other members of the SM Rookies program to debut as members of [[NCT (band)|NCT]] and its first subgroup, NCT U. On April 9, Mark, alongside [[Lee Tae-yong|Taeyong]], Doyoung, [[Ten (singer)|Ten]] and Jaehyun debuted with the digital single \"The 7th Sense\", which he and Taeyong participated in the writing of.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201604061758581112853_2|title=NCT U confirms lineup, set to unveil singles 'The 7th Sense,' 'Without You'|last=Son|first=Ji-hyoung|date=April 6, 2016|publisher=[[The Korea Herald]]|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, SM confirmed Mark as a member of NCT's second subgroup, [[NCT 127]], alongside Taeyong, Taeil, Yuta, Jaehyun, Winwin and Haechan. NCT 127 made their official debut with ''[[NCT 127 (EP)|NCT #127]]'' and title track \"Fire Truck\" on July 10, 2016.<ref name=genre>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201607101242101223011_1|title=NCT 127 \uc804\uace1 \uc74c\uc6d0 \uacf5\uac1c, \ubcf4\ub108\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub799\uae4c\uc9c0 \ucd1d 7\uace1 \uc218\ub85d|date=July 10, 2016|website=Herald Corporation|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, SM confirmed Mark as a member of NCT's third subgroup, [[NCT Dream]], alongside Renjun, Jeno, Haechan, Jaemin, Chenle and Jisung. The group made their official debut on August 24, 2016, with the single \"Chewing Gum\".\n\nIn September 2016, Mark featured on [[Henry Lau]]'s \"Going Through Your Heart\", an original soundtrack for the [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] drama, [[Sweet Stranger and Me]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/909461wpp/henry-ncts-mark-plus-kim-jong-kook-sing-ost-man-living-house|title= Henry And NCT\u2019s Mark Plus Kim Jong Kook To Sing OST For \"The Man Living In Our House\"|date=October 24, 2016|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref> This marked his first solo endeavour since debuting under NCT. \n \nIn January 2017, Mark joined ''[[High School Rapper]]'', a survival hip hop reality TV show which aired on [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]].<ref name=\"crap-source1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/935159wpp/ncts-mark-audition-mnets-new-hip-hop-show-high-school-rapper|title= NCT\u2019s Mark To Audition For Mnet\u2019s New Hip Hop Show \"High School Rapper\"|date=January 9, 2017|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref> He made it to the finals and performed an original song, \"Drop\" featuring labelmate, [[Kang Seul-gi|Seulgi]] of [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]. He subsequently placed 7th overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/967909wpp/watch-high-school-rapper-reveals-final-winner-performances-special-guests|title= Watch: \"High School Rapper\" Reveals Final Winner And Performances With Special Guests|date=April 1, 2017|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Mark collaborated with Exo's [[Xiumin]] on single, [[Young & Free]]. The single was released through [[SM Station Season 2|Season 2]] of SM Entertainment's digital music project [[SM Station]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/music/now/read?oid=311&aid=0000749346|title=\uc5d1\uc18c \uc2dc\uc6b0\ubbfc\u00b7NCT \ub9c8\ud06c, 'SM\uc2a4\ud14c\uc774\uc158'\uc73c\ub85c \uc2a4\ud398\uc15c \ub4c0\uc624 \uacb0\uc131|access-date=2017-06-29|language=ko}}</ref> In the same month, Mark appeared in the first season of the music variety show ''Snowball Project''. He teamed up with [[Park Jae-jung (singer)|Park Jae-jung]] and released \"Lemonade Love\" on July 21, also through SM Station, which was produced by former labelmate Henry Lau and [[Yoon Jong-shin]].<ref name=\"snowballproject\">{{cite web |title=\"\ub208\ub369\uc774 \ucd9c\uaca9\"...\ubc15\uc7ac\uc815X\ub9c8\ud06c, \u2018\ub808\ubaa8\ub124\uc774\ub4dc \ub7ec\ube0c\u2019 \uc624\ub298(21\uc77c) \ubc1c\ud45c |url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/014/0003847621 |website=n.news.naver.com |accessdate=June 30, 2019 |language=ko |date=July 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/2017/05/23/sm-mystic-entertainment-team-new-music-variety-show/|title=Parc Jae Jung And NCT's Mark Are The First Team-Up For SM And Mystic Entertainment's New Variety Show {{!}} Soompi|website=www.soompi.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Mark was named as one of the main emcees of the music program ''[[Show! Music Core]]''. He subsequently left the program in January 2019 to focus on activities with NCT 127.<ref name=\"showmucic\">{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=213&aid=0001014733|title=\uc639\uc131\uc6b0\u00b7\ubbf8\ub098\u00b7\ub9c8\ud06c, '\uc74c\uc545\uc911\uc2ec' \u65b0 MC \ubc1c\ud0c1 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|date=January 26, 2018|website=Herald Corporation|language=ko}}</ref>\nIn May 2018, he became a regular cast member on the [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] reality TV show ''[[It's Dangerous Beyond The Blankets]]''.<ref name=\"blankets\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201805031602080410|title=MBC \uce21 \"NCT \ub9c8\ud06c \u2018\uc774\ubd88\ubc16\uc740 \uc704\ud5d8\ud574\u2019 \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ub17c\uc758\uc911\"|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, Mark released the song \"Dream Me\" with Red Velvet's [[Joy (singer)|Joy]] for the soundtrack of the KBS drama ''[[The Ghost Detective]].''\n\nOn December 31, 2018, Mark became the first member to officially graduate from NCT Dream.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=109&aid=0003850884|title=\"[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] NCT \ub9c8\ud06c, \uc62c\ud574 \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9\uc73c\ub85c NCT DREAM \uc878\uc5c5\u2026\uc878\uc5c5\uc1a1 \uc218\ub85d\"|date=August 26, 2018|accessdate=July 1, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 2019, Mark was confirmed as a member of [[SuperM]], a \"K-pop supergroup\" created by SM Entertainment in collaboration with [[Capitol Records]]. The group's promotions began in October and were  focused at the American market.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Jeff Benjamin |title=Super M, 'The Avengers Of K-Pop,' Unveiled By SM Entertainment And Capitol Music Group |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/08/07/super-m-the-avengers-of-k-pop-unveiled-by-sm-entertainment-and-capitol-music-group/#355dfa061381 |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Forbes |date=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SM Entertainment and Capitol Records Team Up to Launch Super M |url=https://www.billboard.com/video/bbnews080819tiffanykpop2-8526949 |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Billboard |date=8 August 2019}}</ref> SuperM's [[SuperM (EP)|self-titled debut EP]] was released on October 4, 2019 with lead single \"Jopping\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8532879/superm-the-1st-mini-album-billboard-200-no-1|title=SuperM Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart With 'The 1st Mini Album'|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was announced by SM Entertainment that Mark would return to and take part in NCT Dream future activities, as the sub-unit was to be re-branded and shifted away from its previous age-based graduation system.<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9357513/nct-dream-new-album-reload-return-of-mark</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|NCT discography|SuperM#Discography}}\n\n===Songs===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! colspan=\"2\" | Peak chart<br />positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Sales\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Album\n|-\n!  style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%\" |[[Gaon Music Chart|KOR<br />Gaon]]<br /><ref name=\"Gaon\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/|title=Gaon Chart|website=[[Gaon Chart]]|language=ko}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%\" |[[Billboard charts|US<br />World]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/world-digital-songs|title=World Digital Songs|work=[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n|-\