r.\"\"}}</ref>\n<ref name=haughton2006>{{cite book| last=Haughton| first=Brian| title=Hidden History: Lost Civilizations, Secret Knowledge, and Ancient Mysteries| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=awF5hqJpErAC&pg=PA43| accessdate=16 May 2011| date=26 December 2006| publisher=Career Press| isbn=978-1-56414-897-1| pages=43\u201344}}</ref>\n<ref name=ieeecomp1>{{Cite journal| journal= Computer| volume=2011-7| issue=7| pages=32\u201339| date=July 2011|  last1=Edmunds| first1=Mike G.| last2=Freeth| first2=Tony| title=Using Computation to Decode the First Known Computer |doi=10.1109/MC.2011.134}}</ref>\n<!---<ref name=imdb-stonehenge>{{cite web| title=IMDB (2010) \u2013 ''Stonehenge Apocalypse (2010)''| url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1488598/}}</ref>{{unreliable source|date=August 2018}}--->\n<ref name=\"iol\">{{cite news | url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=588&art_id=vn20060606235853817C767629 | title=Ancient 'computer' starts to yield secrets | work=IOL: Technology | date=7 June 2006 | accessdate=16 July 2017 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313113640/http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=588&art_id=vn20060606235853817C767629 | archivedate=13 March 2007 | publisher=Independent Media}}</ref>\n<ref name=isaw-1>{{Cite web |url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/awdl/isaw/isaw-papers/4/images/figure04.jpg |title=The Cosmos on the front of the Antikythera Mechanism |access-date=21 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517031340/http://dlib.nyu.edu/awdl/isaw/isaw-papers/4/images/figure04.jpg |archive-date=17 May 2018 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\n<!--unused<ref name=johnston-06>{{Cite news| last=Johnston| first=Ian| title=Device that let Greeks decode solar system| work=The Scotsman| date=30 November 2006| url=http://news.scotsman.com/international.cfm?id=1774262006| accessdate =26 June 2007}}</ref>-->\n<ref name=lazos-94>{{Cite book| author=Lazos, Christos| date=1994| title= The Antikythera Computer| publisher= AEOLUS PUBLICATIONS GR}}</ref>\n<ref name=marchant-06>{{cite journal| last=Marchant| first=Jo| title=In search of lost time| journal=Nature| date=30 November 2006| volume=444| number=7119| pages=534\u2013538| doi=10.1038/444534a| pmid=17136067| bibcode=2006Natur.444..534M| doi-access=free}}</ref>\n<ref name=papyrus>An extract from a 2nd or 3rd century AD papyrus (P.Wash.Univ.inv. 181+221) about an \"Astrologer's Board\", where the astrologer lays out particular stones to represent the Sun, Moon and planets</ref>\n<ref name=price-74>{{cite journal| last=Price| first=Derek de Solla| title=Gears from the Greeks. The Antikythera Mechanism: A Calendar Computer from ca. 80 B. C.| journal=Transactions of the American Philosophical Society |series=New Series| volume=64| number=7| date=1974| pages=1\u201370| doi=10.2307/1006146| jstor=1006146}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Freeth_SA\">{{cite journal|last1=Freeth|first1=Tony|title=Decoding an Ancient Computer|journal=[[Scientific American]]|volume=301|issue=6|url=http://www.cs.virginia.edu/~robins/Decoding_an_Ancient_Computer.pdf|date=December 2009|page=78|accessdate=26 November 2014|bibcode=2009SciAm.301f..76F|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican1209-76|pmid=20058643}}</ref>\n<ref name=seaman-11>{{cite book| last1=Seaman| first1=Bill| first2=Otto E.| last2=R\u00f6ssler| title=Neosentience: The Benevolence Engine| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wfOBzvKCc5IC&pg=PT111| accessdate=28 May 2013| date=1 January 2011| publisher=Intellect Books| isbn=978-1-84150-404-9| page=111| quote=Mike G. Edmunds and colleagues used imaging and high-resolution X-ray tomography to study fragments of the Antikythera Mechanism, a bronze mechanical analog computer thought to calculate astronomical positions}}</ref>\n<ref name=swedinFerro2007>{{cite book| first1=Eric G.| last1=Swedin |authorlink1=Eric G. Swedin | first2=David L.| last2=Ferro| title=Computers: The Life Story of a Technology| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IJXYoPiwvOMC&pg=PA1| accessdate=28 May