kythera2012|title=Videos|author=The Antikythera Mechanism Research Project|website=YouTube|accessdate=24 July 2017}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120423161138/http://www.hpdst.gr/events/exhibitions/antikythera-mechanism The Antikythera Mechanism Exhibitions] by ''National Hellenic Research Foundation''.\n* [http://demonstrations.wolfram.com/AntikytheraMechanism/ Antikythera Mechanism] at [[Wolfram Research|Wolfram Demonstrations Project]].\n* [http://members.chello.nl/o.veenstra3/vrml/yaas_info/yaas_info.html YAAS - Een 3D interactive virtual reality simulator in VRML]\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MqhuAnySPZ0|title=Virtual Reconstruction of the Antikythera Mechanism (by M. Wright & M. Vicentini)|date=25 August 2009|publisher=[[Heritage Key]]<!-- |accessdate=24 July 2017 -->|via=YouTube}}\n* [http://www.nature.com/nature/videoarchive/antikythera/ Antikythera] ([[Adobe Flash]]) ''Nature'', 30 July 2008\n\n{{Greek astronomy}}\n{{National Archaeological Museum of Athens}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Antikythera Mechanism}}\n[[Category:3rd-century BC works]]\n[[Category:2nd-century BC works]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC works]]\n[[Category:1902 archaeological discoveries]]\n[[Category:1902 in Greece]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek astronomy]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek science]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek technology]]\n[[Category:Analog computers]]\n[[Category:Archaeoastronomy]]\n[[Category:Archaeological artifacts]]\n[[Category:Archaeological discoveries in Greece]]\n[[Category:Astronomical instruments]]\n[[Category:Greek inventions]]\n[[Category:Hellenistic engineering]]\n[[Category:History of computing]]\n[[Category:History of ideas]]\n[[Category:History of mathematics]]\n[[Category:History of science]]\n[[Category:Mechanical calculators]]\n[[Category:Mechanical computers]]\n[[Category:Mysteries]]\n[[Category:National Archaeological Museum of Athens]]\n[[Category:Out-of-place artifacts]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 4 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antikythera_mechanism"}
{"title_page": "Yesterday's Hero (John Paul Young song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Yesterday's Hero\n| cover      = Yesterday's_Hero_(song)_by_John_Paul_Young.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[John Paul Young]]\n| album      = [[Hero (John Paul Young album)|Hero]]\n| released   = 10 February 1975\n| format     = Vinyl, 7\", Single\n| recorded   = 1974\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 3:43\n| label      = [[Albert Productions]]. [[Ariola]]\n| writer     = [[Harry Vanda]], [[George Young (rock musician)|George Young]]\n| producer   = [[Harry Vanda]], [[George Young (rock musician)|George Young]]\n| prev_title = Show and Tell\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[The Love Game (John Paul Young song)|The Love Game]]\n| next_year  = 1975\n}}\n\n\"'''Yesterday's Hero'''\" is a pop song by [[John Paul Young]]. The song was written by [[George Young (rock musician)|George Young]] and [[Harry Vanda]] and was released in February 1975 as the lead single from Young's debut studio album, ''[[Hero (John Paul Young album)|Hero]]'' (1975).\n\nThe song became a worldwide hit, peaking at No. 8 in Australia, No. 1 in South Africa and No. 41 in the United States.\n\n== Overview ==\n\"Yesterday's Hero\" is a song about the fleeting nature of pop stardom. It drew on Vanda & Young's own experiences as former [[teen idols]].<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-McF-1|[1]]][[John Paul Young#cite note-Milesago-2|[2]]][[John Paul Young#cite note-APRA Yesterdays-16|[16]]]</sup>\n\nThe song gave Young his first top ten hit,<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Kent-10|[10]]]</sup> reaching No. 8 on the Australian singles chart<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Kent-10|[10]]]</sup> and staying at No. 1 on the [[Melbourne, Victoria|Melbourne]] charts for six weeks before being replaced by [[Hush (band)|Hush]]'s \"[[Bony Moronie|Boney Maroney]]\". The single sold strongly in the United States, where it reached No. 44 on the [[Cash Box]] Top 100 in February 1976.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-17|[17]]]</sup>\n\nOne of the key factors in the Australian success of \"Yesterday's Hero\" was the film clip made to promote it, which enabled the song to be given heavy exposure on ''[[Countdown (Australian TV series)|Countdown]]'', which had just switched to its new one-hour Sunday evening format, following the official start of [[Colour television|colour TV]] broadcasting on 1 March 1975.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Milesago-2|[2]]][[John Paul Young#cite note-Jeff-18|[18]]][[John Paul Young#cite note-Dave-19|[19]]]</sup> Young's debut performance on ''Countdown'' had him miming \"Yesterday's Hero\" while dressed in a sailor's suit surrounded on an island stage with a studio audience of screaming teen girls.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Long-20|[20]]]</sup> He was dragged off the stage three times by audience members and the microphone cord was ripped out but the song continued uninterrupted.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Long-20|[20]]]</sup> [[ABC Television|ABC TV]] producer, Michael Shrimpton believes his show, ''Countdown'', played a big part in making \"Yesterday's Hero\" and Young a teen pop success.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Jeff-18|[18]]]</sup>\n\n== Track listing ==\n'''7\"''' (AP-10688) / (Ariola 16631 AT)\n*Side A \"Yesterday's Hero\" - 3:43\n*Side B \"The Next Time\" - 3:30\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n;John Paul Young\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1975\u201377)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n| Australian ([[Kent Music Report]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n| Canada ''RPM'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|54\n|-\n| South Africa <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(Y).html|title=South African Rock Lists Website \u2013 SA Charts 1969\u20131989 Acts (Y)|work=South Africa's Rock Lists|publisher=South African Rock Encyclopedia|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Sweden|10|artist=John Paul Young|album=Yesterday's Here|refname=|accessdate=15 February 2016}}\n|-\n|-\n| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard Hot'' 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref><ref>https://www.discogs.com/John-Young-Yesterdays-Hero-The-Next-Time/release/3558979</ref><ref>[http://www.australianmusicdatabase.com/recordings/yesterday-s-hero-b-w-the-next-time-by-john-paul-young Australian Music Database]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|}\n;Bay City Rollers\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1975-76)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Austria \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|Germany \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n| Japan\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n|US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - ISBN 0-89820-089-X</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|54\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100\n|align=\"center\"|49\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (1975)\n!scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Australia <ref>{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, NSW]]|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}} NOTE: Used for Australian Singles and Albums charting from 1970 until [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] created their own [[ARIA Charts|charts]] in mid-1988.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 32\n|-\n|South Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1977|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_19__.html|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Bay City Rollers]] (1976)\n* [[Gene Pitney]] did not cover this song. It's of the same name but was released 10 years earlier.\n* Ignatius Jones (1992)\n* Serbian band [[Laki Pingvini]] covered the song as \"Ne, nisam tvoj heroj\" on album \"Muzika za mlade\" 1984.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{John Paul Young}}\n\n[[Category:1975 singles]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Harry Vanda]]\n[[Category:Songs written by George Young (rock musician)]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Harry Vanda]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Young (rock musician)]]\n[[Category:John Paul Young songs]]\n[[Category:Bay City Rollers songs]]\n[[Category:Paul Nicholas songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Yesterday's Hero\n| cover      = Yesterday's_Hero_(song)_by_John_Paul_Young.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[John Paul Young]]\n| album      = [[Hero (John Paul Young album)|Hero]]\n| released   = 10 February 1975\n| format     = Vinyl, 7\", Single\n| recorded   = 1974\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 3:43\n| label      = [[Albert Productions]]. [[Ariola]]\n| writer     = [[Harry Vanda]], [[George Young (rock musician)|George Young]]\n| producer   = [[Harry Vanda]], [[George Young (rock musician)|George Young]]\n| prev_title = Show and Tell\n| prev_year  = 1974\n| next_title = [[The Love Game (John Paul Young song)|The Love Game]]\n| next_year  = 1975\n}}\n\n\"'''Yesterday's Hero'''\" is a pop song by [[John Paul Young]]. The song was written by [[George Young (rock musician)|George Young]] and [[Harry Vanda]] and was released in February 1975 as the lead single from Young's debut studio album, ''[[Hero (John Paul Young album)|Hero]]'' (1975).\n\nThe song became a worldwide hit, peaking at No. 8 in Australia, No. 1 in South Africa and No. 41 in the United States.\n\n== Overview ==\n\"Yesterday's Hero\" is a song about the fleeting nature of pop stardom. It drew on Vanda & Young's own experiences as former [[teen idols]].<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-McF-1|[1]]][[John Paul Young#cite note-Milesago-2|[2]]][[John Paul Young#cite note-APRA Yesterdays-16|[16]]]</sup>\n\nThe song gave Young his first top ten hit,<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Kent-10|[10]]]</sup> reaching No. 8 on the Australian singles chart<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Kent-10|[10]]]</sup> and staying at No. 1 on the [[Melbourne, Victoria|Melbourne]] charts for six weeks before being replaced by [[Hush (band)|Hush]]'s \"[[Bony Moronie|Boney Maroney]]\". The single sold strongly in the United States, where it reached No. 44 on the [[Cash Box]] Top 100 in February 1976.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-17|[17]]]</sup>\n\nOne of the key factors in the Australian success of \"Yesterday's Hero\" was the film clip made to promote it, which enabled the song to be given heavy exposure on ''[[Countdown (Australian TV series)|Countdown]]'', which had just switched to its new one-hour Sunday evening format, following the official start of [[Colour television|colour TV]] broadcasting on 1 March 1975.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Milesago-2|[2]]][[John Paul Young#cite note-Jeff-18|[18]]][[John Paul Young#cite note-Dave-19|[19]]]</sup> Young's debut performance on ''Countdown'' had him miming \"Yesterday's Hero\" while dressed in a sailor's suit surrounded on an island stage with a studio audience of screaming teen girls.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Long-20|[20]]]</sup> He was dragged off the stage three times by audience members and the microphone cord was ripped out but the song continued uninterrupted.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Long-20|[20]]]</sup> [[ABC Television|ABC TV]] producer, Michael Shrimpton believes his show, ''Countdown'', played a big part in making \"Yesterday's Hero\" and Young a teen pop success.<sup>[[John Paul Young#cite note-Jeff-18|[18]]]</sup>\n\n== Track listing ==\n'''7\"''' (AP-10688) / (Ariola 16631 AT)\n*Side A \"Yesterday's Hero\" - 3:43\n*Side B \"The Next Time\" - 3:30\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n;John Paul Young\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1975\u201377)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n| Australian ([[Kent Music Report]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n| Canada ''RPM'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|54\n|-\n| Japan\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| South Africa <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(Y).html|title=South African Rock Lists Website \u2013 SA Charts 1969\u20131989 Acts (Y)|work=South Africa's Rock Lists|publisher=South African Rock Encyclopedia|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Sweden|10|artist=John Paul Young|album=Yesterday's Here|refname=|accessdate=15 February 2016}}\n|-\n|-\n| US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard Hot'' 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref><ref>https://www.discogs.com/John-Young-Yesterdays-Hero-The-Next-Time/release/3558979</ref><ref>[http://www.australianmusicdatabase.com/recordings/yesterday-s-hero-b-w-the-next-time-by-john-paul-young Australian Music Database]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|}\n;Bay City Rollers\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1975-76)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Austria \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|15\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|Germany \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - ISBN 0-89820-089-X</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|54\n|-\n|US [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100\n|align=\"center\"|49\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"| Chart (1975)\n!scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| Australia <ref>{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, NSW]]|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}} NOTE: Used for Australian Singles and Albums charting from 1970 until [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]] created their own [[ARIA Charts|charts]] in mid-1988.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 32\n|-\n|South Africa <ref>{{cite web|title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1977|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_19__.html|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Bay City Rollers]] (1976)\n* [[Gene Pitney]] did not cover this song. It's of the same name but was released 10 years earlier.\n* Ignatius Jones (1992)\n* Serbian band [[Laki Pingvini]] covered the song as \"Ne, nisam tvoj heroj\" on album \"Muzika za mlade\" 1984.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{John Paul Young}}\n\n[[Category:1975 singles]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Harry Vanda]]\n[[Category:Songs written by George Young (rock musician)]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Harry Vanda]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by George Young (rock musician)]]\n[[Category:John Paul Young songs]]\n[[Category:Bay City Rollers songs]]\n[[Category:Paul Nicholas songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "JGabbard", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:rearr.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yesterday%27s_Hero_(John_Paul_Young_song)"}
